{[%evp 0,39,26,26,26,-6,0,0,16,18,21,25,31,13,27,32,42,35,26,6,6,-24,-9,16,11,3,9,17,48,53,51,56,65,49,57,64,53,41,101,101,96,109]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 c6 4. O-O Bg4 {This is nearly the most common way of development in Reti. The current position might be reached with different move orders.} 5. d4 {I like starting with this natural move. White eliminates the early ...e7-e5. Many Reti fans prefer d2-d3 instead, but occupying the center is the most promising strategy in most cases.} ({In my opinion, after} 5. h3 Bxf3 6. Bxf3 e5 7. d3 Bc5 {Black's strong pawn center compensates for White's bishop pair, so hardly White pretends on much here.}) 5... e6 (5... Nbd7 {Mostly leads to transposition, but there is also a separate case:} 6. h3 Bxf3 ({Worth attention is a rare} 6... Bf5 7. c4 e6 8. Nc3 h6 ({After} 8... Bd6 9. Nh4 Bg6 10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. Qd3 O-O 12. Rd1 $14 {White has a traditional advantage because of bishop pair. The e2-e4 push will follow at the proper moment.}) 9. Qb3 Qb6 {This time the f5-bishop is secured, so Nf3-h4 is pointless.} 10. c5 $1 {A well-timed advance. Black is missing developed pieces, and it makes it tougher to play ...b7-b6.} Qa6 {This position occurred in Shimanov,A - Motylev,A Moscow 2015} (10... Qxb3 11. axb3 {Opens the a-file in White's favor.} a6 12. b4 Rc8 13. g4 Bh7 14. Bf4 Be7 15. Nd2 $1 $14 {The knight moves towards a5. Black was doomed to passive defense in Banusz,T -Damljanovic,B Hungary 2021}) {Here, my natural improvement over White's play is} 11. Bf4 $1 $146 b6 ({After} 11... Be7 12. Rfc1 {vacating f1 for the bishop!} b6 13. Bf1 Qb7 14. g4 Bh7 15. a4 $1 O-O 16. a5 $36 {The poor placement of the black queen causes Black serious problems.}) 12. cxb6 axb6 ({After} 12... Qxb6 13. Na4 Qxb3 14. axb3 $36 {Black's q-side pawns are very vulnerable.}) 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Nd7 15. e4 $14 {Black still has to solve his issues with development.}) (6... Bh5 7. c4 e6 {transposes to the main line.}) 7. exf3 $5 {I like this original approach: White accepts the double pawns to maintain the tension.} (7. Bxf3 {is well met by} e5 $1 {Black seems to be close to equality.}) 7... e6 8. b3 $1 {White prepares c2-c4, so Black's counter-attacking abilities in the center will be restricted.} Be7 ({After} 8... Bd6 9. c4 O-O 10. f4 h5 11. Be3 Qb8 12. Qc2 h4 13. Nc3 a5 14. Ne2 hxg3 15. fxg3 $14 {Black didn't achieve much by advancing the h-pawn, and White has a long-termed positional advantage. Szczepanski,Z - Florea,M ICCF email 2016}) 9. c4 O-O 10. f4 dxc4 $5 {An interesting decision - Black is aiming to unbalance the position.} ({After something like} 10... Rc8 11. Nc3 Re8 12. c5 $14 {It will be a game for two results only as Black lacks any counterplay.}) 11. bxc4 Nb6 12. Na3 Qd7 13. c5 $1 Nbd5 14. Bb2 {The d5-knight is strong, but the other knight is rather useless. At the same time, White's knight is heading on e5.} b6 {The natural play by both sides led to this position in Gunina,V - Pogonina,N Novosibirsk 2016 Here White could have seized the initiative by sacrificing a pawn:} 15. Nc4 $5 $146 bxc5 16. dxc5 Bxc5 17. Qc2 Nb4 18. Qa4 $44 {The c6-pawn is weak, and both White's bishops are powerful.}) 6. h3 Bh5 {This is the most common choice.} (6... Bxf3 7. Bxf3 Nbd7 {yields Black a solid but rather passive position.} 8. c4 dxc4 {This is the most challenging move for White - after all, the pawn is a pawn!} ({After} 8... Bd6 9. Nd2 O-O 10. e4 dxe4 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Bxe4 {The bishop pair and definite space advantage put Black under long-termed positional pressure. For instance,} Nf6 13. Bg2 Re8 14. Qb3 Qc7 15. Bg5 $14 {Hakobyan,A - Andriasian,Z Yerevan 2020}) (8... Be7 {leads to approximately the same scenario :} 9. Nd2 O-O 10. e4 dxe4 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Bxe4 Bf6 {This was Mikhalevski,V - Seletsky,G Chess.com INT 2021 Now White should have played} 13. Be3 $146 Re8 14. Qb3 $14 {, reaching an optimal setup.}) 9. Nd2 Nb6 {Black is playing consistently.} 10. e3 Bb4 11. Qc2 Bxd2 12. Bxd2 O-O {1/2 (17) Korley,K (2451)-Kevlishvili,R (2536) Long Island City 2022} 13. Rfb1 $146 Nfd5 14. b3 cxb3 15. Rxb3 Qd7 16. a4 $44 {The bishop pair and pressure along the -file provide White long-termed compensation for a pawn. Black's play seems tougher from a practical point of view.}) 7. c4 Nbd7 ({Black's other possibility is} 7... Be7 8. Nc3 O-O {, leaving the b8-knight on its initial spot for a while. In this case, White has all the reasons for occupying e5:} 9. Ne5 $1 Nbd7 ({Somewhat akwward is} 9... Nfd7 10. Nd3 $1 dxc4 11. Nf4 Bg6 {Black's minor pieces are poorly placed, and now White can exploit the vulnerable g6-bishop with} 12. h4 $1 e5 {The only adequate response.} 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Bh3 $1 {Depriving the g6-bishop of f5-square.} Qxd1 15. Rxd1 h5 {A sad necessity. Otherwise, the bishop could be trapped.} 16. Be3 Na6 17. Bd4 {White has a powerful initiative in Svane,R - Korobov,A Chess.com INT 2021}) 10. g4 Bg6 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. Qd3 {This position is similar to the main line, but the queen is placed more flexibly - White can cover the c4-pawn with b2-b3 if needed.} Ne8 {We have been following Matlakov,M - Karjakin,S Wijk aan Zee 2018} (12... dxc4 13. Qxc4 e5 14. dxe5 Nxe5 {took place in Harikrishna,P - Adams,M Shenzhen 2017 Here I mostly like} 15. Qa4 $146 Qc7 ({After} 15... Qb6 16. Be3 Bc5 17. Bf4 Rfe8 18. Qc2 {White is threatening 19.Na4, and Black doesn't have proper compensation for White's bishop pair.}) 16. Bf4 Bd6 17. e3 Ned7 18. Bxd6 Qxd6 19. g5 $14 {Black's knights are well-restricted, and the bishop is strong.}) {Black was trying to switch to some king of Stonewall with ...f7-f5. In my opinion, White can obtain a slight plus with} 13. Bf4 $5 $146 Bd6 14. Bd2 f5 (14... Bc7 15. Rad1 Nd6 16. c5 Ne8 17. e4 $14) 15. g5 $1 {Depring the knights of f6.} Bc7 16. f4 Nd6 17. b3 Ne4 18. e3 $14 {Black's position is very solid but passive. White can try to make some progress on the q-side by pushing ..c4-c5 and b2-b3.}) 8. Qb3 {Not only attacking b7 but also covering the c4.} Qb6 9. Nc3 Be7 (9... Qxb3 10. axb3 Bb4 {, as in Gschiel,A - Weichhart,D Austria 2022 can be well met by} 11. Bf4 $146 O-O 12. g4 Bg6 13. c5 a5 14. Na2 $14 {Black suffers from difficulties with the poor b4-bishop.}) (9... Qb4 {took place in Grigorjev,I - Bluebaum,M Chess.com INT 2021 here I suggest the following standard approach:} 10. g4 $146 Bg6 11. c5 $1 {White grabs lots of space and forces Black to liquidate in the endgame in unfavorable redaction.} Qxb3 12. axb3 Be7 13. b4 {A logical follow-up: the b4-b5 push will put strong pressure on c6.} Ne4 14. Nd2 $1 {A decent move: the e4-knight is Black's most active piece, so White reacts properly.} Nxd2 15. Bxd2 {Black cannot prevent b4-b5.} O-O 16. b5 e5 17. e3 Bf6 18. Ra4 $14 {Black's q-side is under strong pressure.}) 10. Nh4 {The main idea of this original maneuver is forcing the exchange of the h5-bishop.} ({It is hardly a good moment for locking the center with} 10. c5 {because of} Qa6 $1 11. g4 Bg6 12. Nh4 b6 13. cxb6 Qxb6 {Black was fine in Adly,A - Marcelin,C Wijk aan Zee 2006}) 10... O-O {The most natural response.} ({The altenratives are:} 10... Ne4 {An ambitious attempt to complicate the matters.} 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Bxe4 Bxe2 ({Worse is} 12... Bxh4 $6 13. gxh4 Qxd4 14. Qxb7 O-O 15. Qxc6 Nf6 ({After} 15... Ne5 16. e3 $1 {White manages to liquidate into a winning endgame.}) (15... Rac8 16. Be3 Rxc6 17. Bxd4 Rxc4 18. e3 e5 19. Bd5) 16. Bd3 $16 {Black didn't have much for two pawns in Mikhalevski,V - Pasman,M Israel 2023}) 13. Re1 Qxb3 14. axb3 Bh5 15. d5 $14 {White's pieces are better mobilized for confrontation in the center.}) ({Too risky is} 10... Qxd4 11. Qxb7 O-O 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Be3 Qb4 {This is the most sensible retreat.} ({Dubious is} 13... Qc4 14. Rac1 {the black queen is in big danger.} Qb4 (14... Rab8 15. Qxa7 $16 {Mikhalevski,V - Mulyar,M Sturbridge 2021}) 15. Qxb4 Bxb4 16. g4 Bg6 17. Nxg6 hxg6 18. Nb5 $16 {White has the bishop pair and good prospects on the c-file.}) 14. Qxb4 Bxb4 15. g4 $1 {An important intermediate move. White covers the e2-pawn with a tempo.} Bg6 16. g5 Ne8 17. Nxg6 hxg6 18. Rfc1 $14 {White has superiority due to bishop pair and control over c-file.}) (10... Rd8 11. cxd5 Nxd5 ({After} 11... cxd5 12. g4 Bg6 13. g5 Nh5 14. Nxg6 hxg6 15. Rd1 $14 {Black struggles to get his poor h5-knight back in play. In the long run, white plans to activate his light-squared bishop with ..e2-e4.}) 12. e4 Nxc3 13. bxc3 c5 {Markus,R -Thompson,B ICCF email 2017 Her White should have continued} 14. Be3 $1 $146 Bxh4 {, not fearing of} 15. gxh4 O-O 16. Rfb1 $36 {Powerful bishops support the strong pawn center, while some structural drawbacks don't tell.}) 11. g4 Bg6 12. Nxg6 hxg6 13. Rd1 {White achieved his goal, and now it is time to defend the central pawn. Text is most flexible as White doesn't block his bishop.} Qa6 {This move looks challenging for White, forcing him to lock the center or release the tension with ..cxd5. On the downside, the a6-queen is now misplaced.} (13... Rfd8 {occure in Pelletier,Y - Baenziger,F Flims 2021 Here I suggest the following new idea:} 14. Bf4 $146 dxc4 ({After} 14... Qa6 15. cxd5 exd5 16. a4 $1 {the positional threat of a4-a5 practically forces Black go liquidate into a slightly worse endgame} Qb6 17. Qxb6 axb6 18. Bf3 $14 {The b6-pawn is vulnerable, and White is planning to push the k-side pawns with h2-h4, g4-g5 e.t.c, Black lacks any constructive counterplay.}) 15. Qxc4 Nd5 {Black builds his play on the vulnerable b2-pawn - from a static point of view, White's chances are preferable.} ({Dubious is} 15... Qxb2 $6 16. Rab1 Nb6 17. Rxb2 Nxc4 18. Rxb7 $16) 16. Na4 $1 {An important intermediate move. White defends the pawn with a tempo.} Qb4 ({Or} 16... Qa5 17. Bd2 Qc7 18. Qb3 $14) 17. Qxb4 Bxb4 18. Bg3 b5 19. a3 $1 {Another intermediate move.} Be7 20. Nc3 $14 {White maintains his positional merits.}) ({Another natural try is} 13... Rad8 14. Qxb6 $1 axb6 {This is now less attractive for Black as the queen's rook isn't on the a-file.} ({After} 14... Nxb6 15. c5 Nbd7 16. Bf4 {Black's position is very cramped, and it is only a matter of time before White will open files on the q-side with ..b2-b4-b5.}) 15. g5 {As usual, this advance diminishes Black's control of e4.} Ne8 ({Worse is} 15... Nh7 16. cxd5 exd5 17. h4 $16 {Black has no compensation for his poor h7-knight.}) 16. cxd5 exd5 17. a4 Nd6 18. b4 $14 {White's unopposite light-squared bishop should tell after ..b4-b5.}) 14. cxd5 exd5 ({in case of} 14... cxd5 15. g5 $1 Ne8 16. e4 dxe4 17. Nxe4 $36 {The strong unopposite g2-bishop offers White a stable positional advantage.}) ({Black's position looks very crumped after} 14... Nxd5 15. e4 Nxc3 16. bxc3 $36 {The massive pawn centre is supported by powerful bishops.}) 15. g5 $1 {The last preparation before the thematic break in the center.} Ne8 ({After} 15... Nh7 16. h4 Rfe8 17. e4 $16 {Black suffers from lack of harmony.}) 16. e4 dxe4 17. Bxe4 {White gains an important tempo in view of the threat of 18.Bxg6.} Kh8 (17... Qb6 18. d5 Qxb3 19. axb3 {also feels very problematic for Black, who fails to set-up blockade:} c5 20. d6 $1 Nxd6 21. Bxb7 $1 {with a collapse,}) 18. d5 Nc5 19. Qb4 Bd6 20. Bg2 $16 {The difference in mobility of pieces put Black on the verge of collapse in Roiz,M - Grinberg,E Netanya 2019} *

