{[%evp 0,33,26,26,23,-6,23,18,25,39,15,13,39,18,31,15,18,3,10,-14,10,-13,6,27,59,46,49,49,52,50,15,15,22,33,33,39]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c6 3. Bg2 Bg4 {This might sometimes transpose to 2...Nf6 with Bg4, but there are also independent cases.} 4. d4 Nd7 (4... Nf6 5. O-O {will get us back to Chapter 1.}) (4... e6 5. O-O Nd7 {is another possible moves order.} (5... Bd6 6. c4)) 5. O-O e6 6. c4 ({Compared to 2...c6 followed by 3...Nf6, I prefer not to start with} 6. h3 Bxf3 7. Bxf3 {because Black can benefit from keeping his knight on g8:} f5 $1 8. Bf4 Be7 9. c4 Ngf6 $11 {The Stone Wall should work well now when the light-squared bishop is gone. Legrand,S - Germanes,R FICGS email 2016}) 6... Bd6 {A flexible way of development. Black takes more control of e5 and keeps his king's knight on its spot for a while. Potentially, Black can still opt for some kind of Stonewall with ...f7-f5.} (6... Ngf6 7. h3 Bxf3 ({Both} 7... Bf5 8. Nc3) ({and} 7... Bh5 {are also covered with 2...c6, 3...Nf6.}) 8. Bxf3 {leads to position that is analyzed in another Chapter.}) ({The original} 6... Be7 7. h3 Bf5 8. Nc3 h6 {was seen in Matamoros Franco,C - Eljanov,P Chess.com INT 2020 Here I suggest the following logical idea:} 9. cxd5 $5 $146 {Black is invited to show his cards.} exd5 ({Dubious is} 9... cxd5 $6 10. Qb3 Qb6 11. Qxb6 Nxb6 12. Nb5 $36 {Black suffers from lack of development and vulnerable a7-pawn.}) 10. Ne5 Ngf6 11. g4 $1 {Black has delayed his development, so White has all the reasons for this extension.} Bh7 12. f4 $1 {The most energetic and consistent. The h7-bishop is in big danger in view of f4-f5.} O-O ({After} 12... Ne4 13. f5 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Bc5+ 15. Kh2 $36 {Black is positionally busted because the h7-bishop is completely out of play.}) 13. Qb3 Qb6 14. Qxb6 Nxb6 ({Worse is} 14... axb6 $6 15. g5 $1 hxg5 16. fxg5 $16) 15. f5 {Now there is no pressure on the central knight, so White finally blocks the h7-bishop.} Rfe8 16. Bf4 $14 {Black is doomed to passive defense because of his poor bishop.}) ({The attempt to switch to Stonewall paths with} 6... f5 $2 {invites a big trouble:} 7. Ng5 $1 Qf6 8. Qb3 h6 9. Nxe6 $1 Qxe6 10. cxd5 Qf6 11. Qxb7 $18 {Black's position was fully destroyed in Alaverdyan,G - Guramishvili,S Jermuk 2010}) ({Hardly can also be recommended} 6... dxc4 7. Qc2 b5 {Black has to play this to justify his previous move.} 8. b3 $1 {A well-timed break. Black is too undeveloped now.} cxb3 9. axb3 Qb6 {The desertion of the light-squared bishop of q-side makes Black's setup very dicey. This was Runic,Z - Mencinger,V Bled 2001 Now the energetic} 10. Ne5 $1 $146 Nxe5 11. dxe5 Ne7 12. Be3 Qb7 13. Bc5 $16 {would put Black on the verge of collapse.}) 7. Nc3 Ngf6 {The most common and natural way of development.} (7... Ne7 {Suleymanli,S - Maghsoodloo,P Chess.com INT 2022 As in the main line, White's most promising way seems} 8. Qb3 $146 Qb6 ({After} 8... Rb8 9. e4 dxc4 10. Qxc4 O-O 11. Rd1 $14 {Black has no compensation for White's superiority in the center.}) 9. c5 Qxb3 10. axb3 Bc7 11. b4 O-O ({In case of} 11... e5 12. e4 $1 {White manages to seize the initiative:} Bxf3 ({Or} 12... dxe4 13. Nxe4 O-O 14. Nd6 $36) 13. Bxf3 exd4 14. Nxd5 cxd5 15. exd5 {Black is positionally busted, even though he is temporarily a piece up.}) 12. b5 e5 {White's play on the q-side is lasting itself, so there is nothing more left for Black.} 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. Bf4 $1 {An important tactical resource that enables White to fully mobilize his forces.} f6 15. dxe5 Bxe5 (15... fxe5 16. Bg5 $36) 16. Bxe5 fxe5 17. h3 Be6 18. b4 $14 {Black doesn't have a sufficient counterplay.}) 8. Qb3 {As usual, claiming the main drawback of early ...Bc8-g4/f5: the b7-pawn might be attacked at an early stage of the game.} Rb8 (8... Qb6 {traditionally runs into} 9. c5 $1 Qxb3 10. axb3 Bc7 11. b4 O-O 12. b5 e5 13. e3 $14 {Black's q-side feels very cramped. Vaulin,A - Pridorozhni,A chessassistantclub.com INT 2004}) 9. Nd2 $1 {A decent move. The g2-bishop is unblocked now, and White can push e2-e4 soon.} O-O 10. e4 e5 {The most challenging move. Black feels ready for confrontation in the center.} (10... dxe4 {leads to a somewhat passive position:} 11. Ndxe4 Bc7 12. Be3 {White's setup looks harmonious now.} Nxe4 13. Nxe4 f5 {This position occurred in Stupak,K - Shirov,A Lichess.org INT 2020 Here I suggest the following attractive idea:} 14. h3 $1 $146 Bxh3 (14... Bh5 $2 {is worse in view of} 15. Ng5 Re8 16. d5 $18) 15. Bxh3 fxe4 16. Bxe6+ Kh8 17. Qc2 $16 {White has a huge positional advantage due to powerful bishops and weak e4-pawn.}) 11. dxe5 dxc4 12. Nxc4 Nxe5 {The natural play by both sides led to this position in Matnadze,A - Alexandrova,O Elista 2004 White should have played} 13. Nxd6 $1 $146 Qxd6 14. h3 Nf3+ ({After} 14... Bf3 15. Bf4 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 $16 {the pin is very dangerous for Black.}) 15. Kh1 Nd4 16. Qc4 Be6 17. Qa4 $36 {White's pawns majority on the q-side is well supported by powerful bishops.} *

