{[%evp 0,21,26,23,28,-6,4,-2,26,6,6,6,19,22,34,36,27,33,32,26,26,26,18,10]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Bg4 3. Bg2 Nd7 {This is by far the most common choice. Black intends to build a pawn center by means of ...e7-e5.} 4. c4 e6 (4... dxc4 $6 {was played by many strong players, but it definitely cannot be recommended.} 5. Na3 e5 {The only attempt to justify the previous move.} ({After both} 5... Nb6 6. Ne5 $16) ({and} 5... c6 6. Nxc4 Ngf6 7. d4 e6 8. Qb3 $16 {Black has no compensation for White's clear superiority in the center.}) 6. Nxc4 e4 ({After} 6... Qe7 7. d3 O-O-O 8. O-O Ngf6 9. Qa4 a6 10. Be3 Nd5 11. Rfc1 $40 {Black's king got under stunning attack in Zhou,W - Negi,P Qinhuangdao 2011}) 7. Nfe5 Be6 {This position occurred in Pick,S - Ptak,P Czech Republic 2013 After the simple} 8. Bxe4 $146 c6 9. Bg2 Nxe5 10. Nxe5 Bd6 11. Nf3 {Black wouldn't have any compensation for a pawn.}) ({In case of} 4... c6 5. cxd5 cxd5 {it becomes clear that the knight belongs to c6.} 6. Nc3 e6 7. O-O {This position was tested in many high-level games. Mostly, White manages to claim superiority because of misplaced d7-knight.} Ngf6 ({There are few alternative ways of handling the position:} 7... Ne7 $5 {This somewhat artificial move isn't as bad as it looks. Black's main idea is placing the knight on c6. Here my natural new idea is} 8. h3 $5 $146 Bh5 ({After} 8... Bxf3 9. Bxf3 Nc6 10. d4 Be7 11. e4 $14 {White manages to open the position and involve the strong light-squared bishop.}) 9. d4 Nc6 10. e4 dxe4 11. Nxe4 Be7 ({After} 11... Nb6 12. g4 $1 Bg6 13. Ne5 {the pressure along h1-a8 diagonal feels very dangerous.}) 12. d5 $1 {A well-timed break. Black cannot set up a blockade on d5.} exd5 13. Qxd5 Bxf3 ({Also after} 13... Nde5 14. Qxd8+ Rxd8 15. Nxe5 Nxe5 16. Nc3 $14 {White has the much better piece coordination.}) 14. Bxf3 Nde5 15. Nc3 $1 {White reasonably accepts the exchange of his bishop- it will cost Black his most active piece.} Nxf3+ 16. Qxf3 O-O 17. Rd1 $14 {Black is under definite pressure because White's knight will land on d5 soon.}) ({Or} 7... Bd6 8. d4 Ngf6 9. Qb3 Qb6 10. Qxb6 Nxb6 ({Also after} 10... axb6 11. Bd2 O-O 12. Nh4 $14 {Black is doomed to passive defense.}) 11. Ne5 Bh5 ({Equally possible is} 11... Bf5 12. f3 $1 {This time White prepares ..e3-e4} h6 13. a4 $1 {The b6-knight is placed awkwardly.} Bxe5 14. dxe5 Nfd7 15. Nb5 $36 {The vulnerability of dark squares made Black's position very difficult in Grandelius,N -Tin,J Chennai 2022}) 12. Bf4 a6 13. h3 $1 {It turns out, that the h5-bishop is still in danger in view of ..g3-g4.} Ke7 14. g4 Bg6 15. Bg5 $36 {Sanal,V - Macias Pino,D Mayrhofen 2022}) 8. Qb3 Bxf3 {Black reasonably decides to swap the minor pieces in order to eliminate the nasty Nf3-e5.} ({In case of} 8... Qb6 9. Qxb6 Nxb6 10. d3 Be7 {White is able to quickly develop a strong initiative on the k-side by means of} 11. Ne5 $1 Bh5 12. h3 O-O 13. g4 Bg6 14. Be3 Nfd7 15. Nxd7 Nxd7 16. f4 $36 {Black's setup feels cramped, especially in view of upcoming ..f4-f5. Ju,W - Munguntuul,B Ankara 2012}) ({Dubious is} 8... Nc5 $6 9. Qb5+ Nfd7 (9... Qd7 10. Ne5 Qxb5 11. Nxb5 {also looks bad.}) 10. d4 a6 11. Qb4 Nd3 12. Qxb7 Nxc1 13. Rfxc1 {Black is missing a pawn, while his Q-side is ruined. Meier,G - Sasikiran,K Berlin 2015}) 9. Bxf3 Qb6 ({After} 9... Nc5 10. Qc2 {White can gain a tempo with d2-d4. For instance,} Rc8 11. d4 Ncd7 12. e4 dxe4 13. Bxe4 $36 {Black suffered from lack of development in Tahbaz,A - Abdilkhair,A Abu Dhabi 2022}) 10. d4 Qxb3 ({After} 10... Bd6 11. e4 dxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Bxe4 $14 {White has a risk-free advantage because of powerful bishops in Berkes,F - Vuckovic,B Budva 2009}) ({Hardly better is} 10... Qxd4 11. Qxb7 Rb8 12. Qa6 $14) 11. axb3 a6 {Black has to parry the threat of Nb5.} 12. e4 dxe4 13. Nxe4 Nd5 {The natural play by both sides led to this position in Petrov,N - Lien,K Reykjavik 2016 Here I like the following plan:} 14. Bd2 $146 Be7 15. Rfc1 O-O 16. Nc3 $14 {Neutralizing White's activity on the q-side isn't easy.}) 5. d4 (5. cxd5 {is much more common. I believe it offers White good prospects due to pawns majority on the k-side. Still, I find the text more manageable as there are many favorable transpositions.}) 5... Bb4+ (5... Ngf6 {is traditionally met by} 6. Qb3 Rb8 7. Nc3 dxc4 8. Qxc4 Bd6 9. O-O O-O 10. h3 Bh5 11. e4 $36 {Black has no compensation for opponent's powerful pawn center.}) (5... c6 {is covered in another Chapter.}) 6. Nc3 ({After} 6. Bd2 Bxf3 7. Bxf3 Bxd2+ 8. Nxd2 c6 {White also has a slight advantage, but the simplifications make Black's defensive task easier.}) 6... Ngf6 {This was Calio,M - Randolph,D ICCF email 2015 Among White's good-looking ideas, I prefer} 7. Qb3 $146 Qe7 (7... c5 8. cxd5 exd5 9. O-O $16 {The isolated d5-pawn causes Black lots of problems.}) (7... a5 8. a3 dxc4 9. Qxc4 Nb6 10. Qb3 Bxc3+ 11. Qxc3 {White has both the superior pawn structure and bishop pair.}) 8. O-O c6 9. a3 {The simplest. White forces a favorable exchange.} Bxc3 10. Qxc3 O-O 11. b3 $14 {The strong unopposed c1-bishop will soon put strong pressure on Black's pieces on the a3-f8 diagonal.} *

