{[%evp 0,37,26,28,28,-6,0,0,18,18,15,12,15,15,11,9,12,-14,-1,-54,-24,-49,15,-39,8,19,45,-6,7,-6,28,33,58,45,35,17,17,-8,-7,-7]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 c6 4. O-O Bf5 {This is Black's second most popular way of development.} 5. d3 e6 6. Nh4 Bg4 {The most challenging move. Black aims to save his light-squared bishop or provoke some weakening moves from White's side.} ({In case of} 6... Bg6 7. Nxg6 hxg6 8. e4 {White's main task is activating the g2-bishop. Black doesn't seem to have any counterplay on the h-file.} Nbd7 (8... dxe4 {occured in Roiz,M - Laznicka,V Plovdiv 2008 and few more games. Here White can favorably change the pawn structure with} 9. d4 $5 $146 Nbd7 (9... c5 10. dxc5 Qxd1 11. Rxd1 Bxc5 12. Nc3 Nbd7 13. Nxe4 $14) 10. Nc3 Be7 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Bxe4 O-O 13. h4 $14 {White has a long-termed positional advantage due to powerful bishops. Among his ideas are ..d4-d5 and h4-h5 breaks.}) 9. exd5 $1 {A well-timed exchange.} Nxd5 ({After} 9... cxd5 10. c4 $1 {White benefits from having an unopposite light-squared bishop. The d5-pawn feels very vulnerable.}) 10. c4 N5f6 11. d4 $14 {Black was doomed to passive defence in Markowski,T - Laznicka,V Polanica Zdroj 2007}) 7. h3 Bh5 8. Qe1 {A flexible move. White unpins the central pawn and overprotects his h4 in view of further ..f2-f4.} Be7 {Eyeing the h4-knight.} ({The other way of development is less sensible:} 8... Nbd7 9. e4 dxe4 10. dxe4 Bc5 11. Kh1 e5 ({Worse is} 11... Qe7 12. f4 O-O-O 13. Nc3 $16 {Markowski,T - Kimmich,B Dresden 2009}) 12. f4 exf4 {Black has to play this to save his h5-bishop - White was threatetning g3-g4 and f4-f5.} 13. gxf4 O-O 14. Nc3 Re8 15. e5 $14 {White has a big space advantage.}) ({Hardly more attractive is also} 8... Bc5 9. e4 O-O 10. Kh1 Na6 11. f4 dxe4 12. dxe4 $14 {Black faced same kind of problems in Vidit,S - Krishna,C Douglas 2018}) (8... Nfd7 {Mostly doesn't have an indepenedent value as after} 9. f4 Bc5+ (9... Be7 {transposes to 9...Nfd7.}) 10. Kh1 f6 11. e4 {White takes the upper hand in the center. For instance,} O-O 12. g4 Bf7 {was seen in Kozul,Z - Martinovic,S Valpovo 2017 At this point, White could have extended on the k-side with} 13. f5 $1 $146 e5 14. Nc3 d4 15. Ne2 Be7 16. Nf3 $36 {Black's king is under strong pressure.}) 9. f4 O-O (9... Nfd7 10. Nf3 Bxf3 ({Too passive is} 10... f6 11. e4 O-O 12. Nc3 Nc5 13. g4 Bf7 14. e5 $14 {Black was very cramped in Gelfand,B - Potkin,V Lichess.org INT 2020}) 11. Bxf3 h5 {A risky attempt to complicate the matters.} (11... O-O 12. e4 {transposes to the main line.}) 12. Bg2 $1 {The most flexible. There is no reason for leaving the f3-bishop to block the rook.} ({Instead, after} 12. e4 dxe4 13. dxe4 h4 14. g4 e5 {Black can try to set up a blockade on the dark squares.}) 12... Na6 13. Nd2 g5 {This is the only way to justify the aggressive h7-h5.} 14. fxg5 Bxg5 {This position occurred in Ganguly,S - Xu,Y Tianjin 2018} 15. e4 $1 $146 Qb6+ 16. Kh2 O-O-O 17. h4 $16 {White's king is safe, while one of Black's pawns seems to fall.}) (9... Nbd7 10. e4 dxe4 11. dxe4 O-O 12. Nd2 Ne8 $146 {Black retreats the knight to play f7-f6 and secure a retreat for his bishop.} ({Equally possible is} 12... Nc5 13. Kh2 Qc7 {Liu,X - Omelja,A Chess.com INT 2022 Now I like the following harmonious way to complete development:} 14. b3 $146 Rad8 15. Bb2 Nfd7 16. Nhf3 $14 {Black's k-side is under permanent pressure in view of further ..g3-g4 and f4-f5.}) 13. b3 $5 {An ambitious approach - White ignores the opponent's positional threat to mobilize all his forces.} Bxh4 14. gxh4 {It turns out, that the c1-bishop has great prospects also on the a3-f8 diagonal.} f6 15. a4 e5 16. Nc4 $14 {White's strong bishops overwhelm the structural drawbacks.}) ({Ineffective is} 9... Na6 10. e4 Nb4 11. Na3 {The active placement of the b4-knight doesn't really bother White. For instance,} a5 {was seen in Platonov,I-Mikenas,V Riga 1970} 12. g4 $1 {white shouldn't fear of ghosts as} Nxg4 13. hxg4 Bxh4 14. Qe2 {leaves Black with no real compensation for a piece.}) 10. e4 Nfd7 {The most consistent. Black moves his knight in advance. White has to do with potential damage of his pawn chain after ...Bxh4.} (10... dxe4 11. dxe4 Nfd7 12. Nf3 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 {transposes to 11...dxe4}) 11. Nf3 {The h4-knight did its job. White has no reason for allowing ...Bxh4.} Bxf3 {Black is reasonably getting rid of the problematic bishop.} ({Another possible plan is} 11... dxe4 12. dxe4 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 e5 {Black aims to fix the pawn structure to neutralize White's bishop pair.} 14. Nd2 Nc5 ({After} 14... Qc7 15. f5 b5 16. Bd1 c5 17. Nf3 $14 {White had decent attacking prospects a-la KID in Hernandez Molina,D - De la Rosa Solorzano,J ICCF email 2020}) 15. Kh2 b5 {We have been following the game Nisipeanu,L - Wojtaszek,R Antalya 2017} 16. Nb3 $1 $146 {In my opinion, White should have regrouped his pieces by means of} Nbd7 17. Nxc5 Nxc5 18. Be3 Qc7 19. f5 $14 {, obtaining the better position due to space advantage and bishop pair.}) ({Equally possible is} 11... f5 12. Be3 fxe4 ({After} 12... Na6 13. Nc3 Nc7 14. Bf2 Kh8 15. Nh2 $14 {White has reached a more harmonious setup, when ..g3-g4 is to follow soon. Demidov,M - Iljushin,A Tuapse 2021}) 13. dxe4 Na6 {took place in Stefanova,A -Tomashevsky,E Doha 2015 White should have developed his pieces most actively with} 14. Nc3 $1 $146 Bc5 15. Bxc5 Naxc5 16. Kh2 Qb6 17. Rb1 $14 {The e6-pawn and somewhat vulnerable king cause Black definite problems.}) 12. Bxf3 a5 {By playing this Black shows his intention to place the knight on a6.} (12... dxe4 13. dxe4 {will get us back to the main line.}) (12... Na6 13. Nc3 Bf6 14. e5 Be7 15. Ne2 Nb4 16. Qd1 $14 {left Black with no real counterplay, while the g8 is under permanent pressure in view of ..g3-g4 and f4-f5. Yu,Y - Har Zvi,R Chess.com INT 2023}) 13. a4 {It makes sense for White to prevent Black from seizing more space with ...a5-a4.} Na6 14. Qe2 {The queen did its job, and now White moves it to cover c2.} Ndc5 15. e5 d4 ({The attempt to stabilize the situation on the k-side with} 15... f5 {doesn't seem to fully solve the issues:} 16. Be3 d4 17. Bf2 Nb4 18. c3 $1 {A strong move. White manages to fully neutralize Black's counterplay on the opposite side.} Nbxd3 (18... dxc3 19. bxc3 Nbxd3 20. Rd1 $16) 19. Bxd4 $36 {Black's knights are rather unstable.}) 16. Nd2 Nb4 17. Ne4 Qb6 {This position occurred in Yakubboev,N - Dmitrenko,V Tashkent 2021 Now the simple} 18. g4 $146 Nxe4 19. Bxe4 {would have put Black's king under strong pressure.} *

