{[%evp 0,33,26,28,23,-6,0,0,18,15,29,3,11,3,30,35,35,-6,11,11,11,11,8,17,49,38,34,30,52,27,32,0,10,17,17,-27]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 c6 4. O-O Bf5 5. d3 h6 {This is Black's second choice, and it was played more than 2000 times. As often happens in the London system (reversed), Black secures h7 for a retreat and emilimates Nf3-h4 ideas.} 6. c4 {I find this response most energetic: since Black wasted a tempo for h7-h6, it makes sense for White to immediately initiate some play in center.} e6 {The most natural and common move.} ({The alternative is} 6... dxc4 7. Ne5 $1 {A powerful tactical resource. White avoids the symmetric pawn structure} (7. dxc4 Qxd1 8. Rxd1 Nbd7 {was proved to be very solid for Black because the f5-bishop is superior over White's bishop.}) 7... Nbd7 ({Too artificial is} 7... Be6 8. Nxc4 Bxc4 9. dxc4 {Black was interested in this pawn structure but conceded the bishop and wasted a tempo.} Qxd1 10. Rxd1 e5 ({Equally possible is} 10... e6 11. Nc3 Nbd7 12. Rb1 a5 13. Na4 $14 {Kengis,E - Vysochin,S Cairo 2003}) 11. Nc3 Nbd7 12. Rb1 a5 13. b3 $14 {White is better developed, and the advance of b-pawn might be dangerous for Black in the long run. Drasko,M - Muratovic,E Zenica 2013}) ({Cannot also be recommended} 7... Qc8 $6 8. Nxc4 Bh3 9. e4 Bxg2 10. Kxg2 c5 11. Nc3 Nc6 12. Be3 $16 {White's development advantage starts to tell. Drasko,M - Matulovic,M Vrnjacka Banja 1991}) ({Of course, the tactical point of White's last move is illustrated in the following case:} 7... cxd3 $6 8. Qb3 e6 9. Qxb7 Nbd7 10. Bxc6 dxe2 11. Re1 $36 {The pinned knight causes Black lots of problems.}) 8. Nxc4 e5 {Black should try to control central squares more.} ({After} 8... e6 9. Bf4 $1 Nb6 10. Nbd2 Be7 11. Na5 Qd7 12. Rc1 O-O 13. Nf3 $36 {Black got under strong positional pressure when his pieces were tied with defending b7. Sundararajan,K - Martynyuk,E Moscow 2018}) 9. Nbd2 $1 {This is the most flexible setup - White connects his knights and leaves the long diagonal unblocked.} ({White achieves nothing special with} 9. Nc3 Be6 10. b3 Be7 $11) 9... Be6 {This was Kengis,E - Feoktistov,A Arta 2004} (9... Be7 {is well met by} 10. b4 $1 O-O 11. a3 Qc7 12. Bb2 Rfe8 13. Rc1 {White has a much more harmonious position when considering both b4-b5 and e2-e4.} a6 14. e4 $1 {By playing this move, White locks his own bishop but restricts nearly all opponent's pieces.} Bg4 15. f3 Bh5 16. Kh1 Rad8 17. Nb3 $14 {Black was doomed to passive defence in Das,A - Mannion,S Hastings 2017}) {Here I strongly recommend} 10. Qc2 $1 $146 b5 ({Hardly better is} 10... Be7 11. Nf3 $1 Qc7 12. d4 exd4 13. Bf4 $36) 11. Ne3 Rc8 12. Nb3 Bd6 13. d4 O-O 14. Rd1 $14 {The permanent weakness of the c6-pawn makes Black's position rather unpleasant.}) 7. Qb3 {A standard approach in Reti with Bg4/Bf5 - the b7-pawn is a kind of issue for Black, and text move often forces Black to play ...Qb6.} Qb6 (7... Qc8 $6 {was played by a few strong players, but it is certainly dubious - the black queen is poorly placed.} 8. cxd5 exd5 9. e4 $1 {The most energetic way of exploiting the lack of harmony in the opponent's camp.} dxe4 10. dxe4 Be6 {A sad necessity. Black had to waste a tempo.} ({The pawn is intouchable:} 10... Nxe4 11. Re1 Be7 12. Nd4 $18) ({Or} 10... Bxe4 11. Re1 Be7 12. Nc3 $18) 11. Qc2 Be7 12. Nd4 Bh3 {The only way to justify 7...Qc8.} 13. e5 Nd5 {This position occurred in Cherepkov,A-Zhukhovitsky,S Leningrad 1957 At this point, White should have continued:} 14. Bxh3 $1 $146 Qxh3 15. Nc3 Nxc3 16. bxc3 O-O 17. Rb1 $16 {Black still struggles to develop his Q-side pieces.}) 8. Qc2 {I like this tricky idea: White deviates from exchanging queens to focus on e2-e4 break. At the same time, the black queen is vulnerable as White's minor pieces can easily attack it.} Nbd7 ({The alternative} 8... Be7 {also runs into} 9. cxd5 exd5 (9... cxd5 {, as in Goganov,A - Sari,Y Konya 2019 can be strongly met by} 10. Be3 $1 $146 Qd8 11. Qb3 $1 {Forcing the weakening b7-b6} b6 12. Rc1 O-O 13. Nc3 $14 {Black has serious problems with completing development because of weak c6-spot.}) 10. Nc3 O-O (10... Nbd7 11. e4 dxe4 12. dxe4 Bh7 {is covered via 8...Nbd7.}) 11. e4 dxe4 (11... Bh7 12. Be3 Qa6 (12... Qd8 13. Qb3 Na6 {took place in Moroni,L - Nikitenko,M Krakow 2019 White shouldn't fear of ghosts and grab the pawn:} 14. Qxb7 $1 $146 Nb4 15. Rfd1 Rb8 16. Qxa7 Ra8 17. Qb6 $16 {Black has no real compensation for missing pawns.}) 13. Rfd1 Nbd7 14. exd5 $1 {A well-timed exchange. Since Black's knight will not be placed on c6, White can benefit from opening the c-file.} cxd5 ({Equally unpleasant for Black is} 14... Nxd5 15. Nxd5 cxd5 16. Qb3 Rfd8 17. Rac1 $36 {Kaidanov,G - Mannion,S Douglas 2018}) 15. Qb3 Rfd8 16. d4 $14 {White's pieces were placed much better in this position with a symmetrical pawn structure. Banusz,T - Braeuer,F Karlsruhe 2018}) 12. dxe4 Bh7 13. Be3 ({This time} 13. Qe2 {isn't effective in view of} Qa6 $1 {, liquidating into an acceptable endgame.}) 13... Qa6 ({Also after} 13... Qa5 14. a3 {Black faces some difficulties with finding a safe spot for his queen. For instance,} Nbd7 15. Rfd1 Rfd8 16. b4 Qh5 17. h3 $14 {Velikov,P - Miljkovic,M Niska Banja 2010}) 14. Rfd1 Nbd7 15. Qb3 $1 {By moving his queen, White makes a strong threat of e4-e5.} Nc5 16. Qb4 Qb6 17. Qc4 $14 {White has superior piece coordination in Jumabayev,R - Ibrayev,N Almaty 2020}) 9. cxd5 $1 {A well-timed exchange. White eliminates the possible ...dxc4 and forces Black to make a tough decision.} cxd5 (9... exd5 {traditionally meets} 10. e4 dxe4 ({After} 10... Bh7 11. e5 Ng4 12. Qe2 $36 {the ugly g4-knight makes Black's position dangerous.}) 11. dxe4 Bh7 12. Nc3 {The pawn majority often means that White will try to develop his initiative on the K-side.} Be7 (12... Bb4 13. Be3 Qa5 ({After} 13... Qa6 14. Nd4 O-O 15. Rfd1 Rad8 16. Nb3 $14 {White has a clear position advantage in view of the poor black queen and locked h7-bishop. Yeoh,L - Mohamad,E Johor 2017}) 14. Nd2 O-O 15. Rfd1 Rfe8 16. Nc4 Qh5 17. f3 $14 {Black's counter-attacking abilities were heavily restricted. Oparin,G - Huda,M Lichess.org INT 2020}) 13. Qe2 $1 {It is a good moment for unpinning the e4-pawn.} Nc5 (13... O-O 14. e5 Nd5 15. e6 $36) 14. Be3 Qa6 15. Qxa6 Nxa6 16. Ne5 O-O 17. f3 $14 {The queen's trade didn't change much - Black is doomed to passive defense. Matlakov,M - Sidhant,M Sharjah 2019}) 10. Nc3 Be7 (10... Rc8 {leaves the a7-pawn vulnerable} 11. Qa4 $1 Bc5 12. e4 dxe4 13. dxe4 Bg6 14. e5 Nh7 15. Rd1 $36 {White had a free initiative because Black's king is stuck in the center. Misericordia,A - Luers,L LSS email 2018}) 11. Be3 {Gaining an important tempo and connecting the rooks.} (11. e4 $5 {also looks like a promising idea.}) 11... Qa6 ({In case of} 11... Qa5 12. Qb3 O-O 13. Qxb7 {Black hardly has sufficient compensation. For instance,} Rfb8 14. Qc6 Qd8 {This was Runarsson,G - Schmalz,P ICCF email 2017 White could have consolidated with} 15. Nd4 $146 Bg6 16. Qa4 Rb4 17. Qd1 Rc8 18. Nb3 $14 {, maintaining the extra pawn.}) 12. Nd4 Bg6 13. Ncb5 {The activity of knights offers White definite initiative on the q-side.} Bd8 {We have been following the game Vantika,A - Adane,N Jaipur 2018 Here I mostly like the following positional approach:} 14. a4 $5 $146 O-O 15. b4 {White's pawns are well restricting Black's minor pieces.} e5 16. Nb3 Bb6 17. Bd2 $14 {Black suffers from poor piece coordination.} *

