{[%evp 0,29,26,28,23,-6,35,18,34,11,24,23,30,26,30,25,30,33,33,30,30,24,23,-9,20,14,24,30,31,31,54,27]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c6 3. Bg2 Bf5 {By choosing this move order, Black often shows his intention to keep the g8-knight on its initial spot for a while. The main benefit of this measure might be eliminating the nasty Nf3-h4 in some cases.} 4. O-O e6 ({Another common move is} 4... Nd7 {Black shows his intention to push e7-e5.} 5. c4 $1 {A decent way to interrupt Black's plans and claim the drawbacks of early ...Nb8-d7.} e6 (5... dxc4 {isn't effective as White can immediately regain the pawn with} 6. Na3 Nb6 7. Ne5 $1 g6 (7... Qd4 {meets} 8. Nexc4 $1 Nxc4 9. Qa4 $14) 8. Naxc4 Bg7 9. a4 ({Good enough is also} 9. d4 $14) 9... Nf6 10. Ne3 Be4 11. f3 Bd5 12. a5 Nbd7 13. d4 $36 {Black got under strong positional pressure because of White's pawn center. Jakovenko,D - Dreev,A Izhevsk 2019}) 6. cxd5 {A well-timed exchange. Obviously, in case Black captures with c-pawn, his knight should be placed on c6.} exd5 (6... cxd5 7. Qb3 Qb6 ({In case of} 7... Nc5 8. Qb4 Rb8 9. d4 Nd7 10. Qa4 $14 {White's pieces are better mobilized, and Black's q-side pawns are somewhat vulnerable.}) 8. Qxb6 axb6 (8... Nxb6 {leads to approximate the same character of play because the b6-knight is awkward :} 9. d3 Nf6 10. Be3 Nc8 11. Nc3 $14 {Aczel,G - Gungl,T Budapest 2020}) 9. Nc3 Ngf6 10. Nd4 Bg6 11. Ndb5 Rc8 12. d3 Be7 13. Bf4 O-O 14. Rac1 $14 {1-0 (29) Meier,G (2623)-Rey,C (2063) Nancy 2019}) 7. d3 Ngf6 8. Nc3 {Of course, White's plan definitely involves e2-e4 from now.} Be7 9. e4 $1 {The most energetic. It turns out that there is no need for preparations.} dxe4 (9... Bg4 10. exd5 cxd5 11. h3 $16 {White's development advantage starts to tell now when the d5-pawn is so weak.}) 10. dxe4 Nxe4 {The only challenging move.} ({After} 10... Bg4 11. h3 Bh5 12. g4 Bg6 13. Nd4 $16 {Black has nothing to do against further extension with f2-f4 and e4-e5.}) 11. Nd4 Nxc3 12. bxc3 Bg6 13. h4 $1 {An important resource - the threat of 14.h5 forces Black to weaken his king.} ({Less promising is} 13. Re1 O-O 14. Bxc6 Qc8 $1 15. Bxb7 Qxb7 16. Rxe7 Rfe8 $44 {Svidler,P - Vitiugov,N Chita 2015}) 13... h5 {The lesser evil, although the h5-pawn is very vulnerable now.} ({After} 13... Nf6 14. Qb3 O-O {A sad necessity - otherwise 14...Qb6 15.Nxc6! is crushing.} 15. Qxb7 $16 {White regained the pawn and maintained all his merits in Gumularz,S - Chyzy,J Krakow 2020}) ({Even worse is} 13... h6 $6 {, as in Meier,G - Reshetnikov,A Moscow 2019 White should have played} 14. h5 $1 $146 Bh7 15. Bxc6 $1 bxc6 16. Nxc6 Qb6 (16... Qc7 17. Nxe7 Kxe7 18. Re1+ Kf8 19. Ba3+ Kg8 20. Qd5 $18 {, followed by 21.Re7 is crushing.}) 17. Nxe7 Kxe7 18. Re1+ Kd8 19. Qg4 $40 {White has a stunning attack.}) 14. Re1 O-O 15. Bxc6 Qc8 16. Bf3 Bf6 17. Bd2 $14 {One of Black's pawns will fall. Black doesn't seem to have sufficient compensation. Emrich,E - Zylla,J GER email 2014}) (4... h6 {doesn't have an independent value as after} 5. d3 {Black has either to play} e6 ({Or} 5... Nf6)) 5. d3 {Now Black is at crossroads.} Be7 {Black develops his bishop and temprarily prevents h4.} (5... Nf6 6. Nh4 {transpososes to 2...Nf6 & 4...Bf5.}) ({After} 5... h6 6. c4 dxc4 (6... Nf6 {transpososes to 2...Nf6 & 4...Bf5.}) {White is able to deviate from trading queens with} 7. d4 $1 Nf6 8. Nbd2 Be7 ({Black cannot defend the pawn with} 8... b5 $2 9. Ne5 Qb6 10. a4 {with a total collapse.}) 9. Nxc4 O-O {We have been following the game Aditya,M - Lazavik,D Tornelo INT 2020 Here White should have played} 10. Nfe5 $146 {, intending to build a strong pawn center with f2-f3 and e3-e4.} Be4 (10... Nbd7 11. Qb3 $14) 11. f3 Bh7 12. Be3 $1 {Completing development and supporting d4.} Qc7 13. Bf2 Nbd7 14. e4 $14 {Black suffers from poor Bh7.}) (5... Bd6 {runs into} 6. e4 $1 Bg6 ({After} 6... dxe4 7. Nh4 Nf6 8. Nxf5 exf5 9. dxe4 fxe4 10. Nc3 $14 {the e4-pawn falls, and White will obtain the better position due to his powerful bishops.}) 7. Nh4 {White exchanges the light-squared bishop in a favorable situation.} Nf6 8. Nxg6 hxg6 9. Nd2 Nbd7 10. Qe2 O-O 11. Nf3 Qc7 12. Re1 $14 {Black got under long-lasting pressure on the K-side. Dahl,I - Mazariegos,S Thessaloniki 1984}) (5... Nd7 {was played twice by strong GM Vladimir Malakhov and others. Curiously, the most energetic} 6. e4 $1 $146 {is already a novelty!} dxe4 7. Nh4 Ngf6 ({Black cannot afford the ''materialistic approach'':} 7... exd3 $2 8. Nxf5 exf5 9. Qxd3 g6 10. Re1+ Be7 11. Qc3 Ngf6 12. Bh6 $18) 8. Qe1 $1 {The opposition on the e-file is quite annoying for Black.} h6 9. Nxf5 ({But not} 9. dxe4 $6 Bh7 $13) 9... exf5 10. dxe4 fxe4 11. Nd2 Be7 12. Nxe4 O-O 13. Be3 $14 {In the semi-open middlegame like that, the bishop pair is always viable.}) 6. Nbd2 {The most flexible move. Black is invited to show his cards now - the most natural 6...Nf6 can be met by 7.Nh4 again.} ({In my opinion,} 6. c4 {is less promising now because of} dxc4 7. dxc4 ({This time after} 7. d4 Nd7 8. Nbd2 {Black can maintain his extra pawn with} b5 9. a4 a6 {White keeps some compensation for a pawn, but hardly it can suffice for more than equality.}) 7... Qxd1 8. Rxd1 Nf6 $11) 6... Nf6 {The most common continuation.} ({I also examined:} 6... h6 $146 7. e4 Bh7 8. e5 $14 {Black struggles to move his Ng8.}) ({After} 6... Nd7 7. e4 Bg6 8. Qe2 Qc7 9. a4 $14 {Black experiences difficulties with developing k-side pieces because of ..e4-e5 push. Lomsadze,D - Kashefi,A Hamedan 2019}) 7. Nh4 $1 {Of course, this has to be played before Black ...h7-h6.} Bg4 {Black is reasonably trying to save his light-squared bishop.} ({The more passive approach is} 7... Bg6 8. Nxg6 hxg6 9. e4 Nbd7 ({After} 9... a5 10. a4 Na6 11. Qe2 $14 {White had both the bishop pair and decent prospects on the k-side. Sanal,V - Celik,H Podgorica 2021}) 10. Qe2 Qc7 11. Re1 dxe4 12. dxe4 e5 13. Nf3 $14 {White was clearly better due to strong unoposed light-squared bishop in Skripchenko,A - Khademalsharieh,S Monte Carlo 2015}) 8. h3 Bh5 9. g4 {This is a traditional way of extending. White shouldn't fear weakening the king a bit.} Bg6 (9... Nfd7 {can be strongly met by} 10. Nf5 $1 exf5 11. gxh5 Nf6 12. e4 $1 {Opening the center as soon as possible is essential.} fxe4 13. dxe4 dxe4 14. Nxe4 O-O 15. Nxf6+ Bxf6 16. Qg4 $14 {The power of bishops overwhelms slight structural drawbacks. Salomon,J - Gagare,S Moscow 2018}) 10. e3 $1 {A clever idea. This modest-looking move is mainly aimed at vacating e2 for White's queen. Also, White prevents the possible ...d5-d4 in the long run.} ({The more straightforward} 10. e4 Nbd7 11. Qe2 Qc7 12. f4 dxe4 13. dxe4 {took place in Mamedyarov,S - Svetushkin,D Germany 2010 Now Black should have bravely played} Bxe4 $1 $146 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Bxe4 Bxh4 {White has some compensation for a pawn, but not more.}) 10... Nbd7 (10... Nfd7 11. Nxg6 hxg6 {occured in Seeman,T - Vovk,I Kardla 2009 Now I suggest the most consistent} 12. Qe2 $146 O-O 13. e4 dxe4 14. Nxe4 Nf6 15. Ng3 $14 {White has decent prospects on the k-side with g4-g5 and h3-h4 to follow.}) 11. Qe2 a5 ({In case of} 11... O-O 12. f4 Qc7 13. Ndf3 Rae8 14. Bd2 $14 {Black's k-side is under permanent pressure, while he fails to make any counterplay on the opposite side.}) 12. f4 O-O {This was Manafov,V - Pogosyan,S Lichess.org INT 2020 White should have continued} 13. Ndf3 $146 Re8 14. Bd2 Bd6 15. Rad1 $14 {, maintaining the pressure on Black's king.} *

