{[%evp 0,37,26,23,23,-6,0,0,6,5,22,6,12,5,19,-2,0,11,0,8,-5,-72,-72,-73,-80,-57,-30,-49,32,-5,24,-35,-4,-4,1,-3,2,0,7,7]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O Be7 5. d3 ({Both} 5. d4) ({and} 5. c4 {are more common, but it takes us to major Catalan paths. I prefer to opt for the sort of Reversed KID, where White can benefit from his flexible setup.}) 5... O-O (5... c5 {mostly leads to the same position as 5...0-0, but sometimes Black deviates from castling.} 6. Bf4 Nc6 7. a4 $5 {An interesting idea. White prevents the possible ...b7-b5 and invites Black to show his cards.} h6 (7... O-O 8. e4 {transposes to the main line.}) (7... b6 8. e4 $146 {This logical continuation is a novelty.} ({Less flexible is} 8. Nc3 Bb7 9. e4 O-O 10. e5 Nd7 11. Re1 a6 $132 {The c3-knight is somewhat misplaced Gajewski,G - Nasuta,G Warsaw 2021}) 8... Bb7 ({After} 8... dxe4 9. dxe4 Ba6 10. Re1 Qxd1 11. Rxd1 O-O 12. Na3 Rfd8 13. Ne5 $14 {This position a-la reversed Exchanged KID is more pleasant for White because of the potential possibility of advancing the ''f'' and ''e'' pawns.}) 9. Na3 dxe4 ({The alternatives are:} 9... O-O 10. e5 Nd7 11. h4 a6 12. Re1 $14 {White has a traditional attacking plan that involves h4-h5-h6. At the same time, Black counter-attacking abilities are questionable.}) ({Approximately the same scenario might happen after} 9... a6 10. c3 h6 11. h4 O-O 12. e5 Nd7 13. Qe2 $14) 10. dxe4 Nxe4 11. Ne5 ({After} 11. Qe2 Nf6 12. Rad1 Qc8 13. Nb5 O-O 14. Nc7 Rb8 {White hardly has anything better than repeating.}) 11... Nxe5 12. Bxe5 Qxd1 13. Raxd1 f6 14. Rfe1 fxe5 15. Bxe4 Bxe4 16. Rxe4 $44 {The engine evaluates this position as almost equal, but the superiority of the knight over Black's bishop makes White's position more pleasant from a human point of view.}) 8. e4 O-O ({Worth attention is} 8... dxe4 $5 9. dxe4 g5 10. Qxd8+ Bxd8 11. Be3 Nxe4 12. Rd1 {White has full compensation for a pawn because of much more active pieces and the weakening ...g7-g5.}) 9. Qe2 b6 {This position occurred in Carlsen,M - Schitco,I Chennai 2022 Here I mostly like the straightforward} 10. e5 $146 Nh7 ({After} 10... Nd7 11. h4 Bb7 12. c3 a6 13. Na3 $14 {Black's k-side is exposed by ...h7-h6.}) 11. h4 Bb7 12. c3 {A clever idea: White not only restricts the c6-knight but also shows his intention to connect the pawn with d3-d4.} Qd7 13. Na3 Na5 14. Nb5 $14 {The black king is under permanent pressure, while Black doesn't have real counterplay for now.}) (5... b6 {Black keeps his king in the center for a while. This flexible move was played by many strong players, including Nakamura, Bacrot and others.} 6. e4 {The sharpest. White is aiming to exploit the vulnerability of long diagonal.} (6. c4 Bb7 7. cxd5 exd5 8. e4 dxe4) 6... dxe4 (6... Bb7 7. e5 Nfd7 8. d4 {might lead to an original position a-la French.} c5 9. c3 Nc6 10. Re1 b5 (10... O-O 11. Bf1 Rc8 12. h4 $36) 11. h4 h6 {The natural play by both sides led to this position in Ni,H - Wang,L China 2014 Here I suggest the following new idea:} 12. Na3 $5 $146 {White involves his queen's knight with a tempo.} b4 ({After} 12... Qb6 13. Nc2 a5 14. Nh2 b4 15. Qg4 $14 {White's play on the k-side is lasting faster than Black's extension on the opposite side.}) 13. Nb5 {Of course, the knight is heading on d6.} O-O 14. Bf4 Rb8 15. Nd6 Bxd6 16. exd6 $14 {The d6-passer is supported by powerful f4-bishop.}) 7. dxe4 $1 {White's most promising way is connected with a pawn sacrifice.} ({Instead,} 7. Ng5 Bb7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Ngxe4 Nxe4 10. Nxe4 Qc8 {was proved to be very solid for the second player.}) 7... Qxd1 (7... Nxe4 {By trading queens, Black doesn't manage to fully neutralize White's initiative:} 8. Qxd8+ Bxd8 9. Nfd2 $1 Nxd2 10. Bxd2 c6 11. Rd1 {White quickly activates all his pieces.} O-O 12. Bb4 Re8 13. Nc3 $36 {Black's Q-side is very cramped.}) 8. Rxd1 Bb7 9. Nc3 $1 Nxe4 {This leads to interesting consequences.} ({After} 9... a6 10. Bf4 Nxe4 11. Nxe4 Bxe4 12. Bxc7 $14 {White regains the pawn and keeps some pressure.}) 10. Ne5 Nxc3 ({After} 10... Nc5 11. Nb5 Nba6 12. Nc6 $36 {The strong white knights dominate Black's pieces.}) 11. Bxb7 Nxd1 12. Bxa8 f6 13. Nd3 c6 {A funny situation when minor pieces of both players are almost trapped!} 14. a4 $1 {This move poses Black the major problems.} e5 ({After} 14... a5 15. Bd2 Nxb2 16. Nxb2 Kd7 17. Nc4 Kc7 18. Nxa5 $1 $14 {White will be able to give up a piece for few pawns in favorable redaction.}) 15. a5 e4 16. axb6 axb6 17. Nf4 {The engine says Black is OK here, but it looks much easier to play with White here because the d1-knight is in big danger, and White has control over a-file.}) (5... Nc6 $5 {many strong grandmasters, including Ian Nepomniatchi, successfully employed this move. Black is aiming to build a pawn center with e6-e5.} 6. a3 $5 {I like this approach. Black is invited to enter reversed Pirc when White is 2 tempi up!} O-O ({After} 6... a5 7. b3 O-O 8. Bb2 {White takes control of long diagonal.} d4 ({After} 8... Bd6 {White can switch to usual ''Catalan'' paths with} 9. d4 Ne7 10. c4 {, and then Black still has issues with the c8-bishop.}) 9. c3 {White takes advantage of his superior development to get rid of annoying d4-pawn.} e5 10. Nbd2 Re8 11. cxd4 exd4 12. Re1 Bc5 13. Qc2 Qe7 {Hickl,J - Chloupek,S Biel 1993} 14. Rec1 $146 Ba7 ({Hardly better is} 14... Bb6 15. Nc4 Ba7 16. b4 $1 {The same method} axb4 17. axb4 Nxb4 18. Qd2 $36 {The pinned a7-bishop doesn't allow Black to keep the extra pawn. After capturing on d4, White will obtain the better position.}) 15. b4 $1 axb4 16. axb4 Qxb4 17. Ba3 Qb5 18. Bc5 $36) ({In case of} 6... e5 7. b4 e4 8. Nfd2 {the lack of development practically forces Black to release the tension and unblock the g2-bishop.} exd3 9. cxd3 O-O 10. Nc3 d4 11. Nce4 Nxe4 12. Bxe4 {White has better chances due to top pressure along the long diagonal. Hoeger,G-Schuster,L DESC email 2016}) 7. b4 $146 {I was surprised to discover that this most natural move is a novelty. Now the c6 feels misplaced.} e5 8. b5 Nd4 9. Nxd4 exd4 10. Bb2 a6 11. a4 $14 {The d4-pawn will fall soon, so White will be pressured due to his fianchettoed bishops.}) 6. Bf4 b6 {Nearly the most natural approach - Black is aiming to harmoniously develop his Q-side pieces.} ({The are few alternatives:} 6... Nc6 7. d4 Bd6 (7... b6 8. c4 Bb7 {took place in Kramnik,V - Aronian,L Leuven 2016 In my opinion, White could have claimed the drawbacks of Black's setup with} 9. cxd5 $146 Nxd5 10. Bd2 Rc8 11. Re1 $14 {The c6-knight is placed awkwardly, so Black cannot challenge the center with ...c7-c5.}) 8. e3 $1 {From now White's strategy is based on preventing the freeing ...e6-e5 and keeping the c8-bishop passive.} Qe7 ({The other way of preparing ....e6-e5 is} 8... Re8 9. Nbd2 e5 10. dxe5 Nxe5 11. Nxe5 Bxe5 12. Bxe5 Rxe5 13. c4 $14 {The vulnerablity of the e5-rook and pressure on the h1-a8 diagonal makes Black's position rather uncomfortable.}) ({Hardly better is} 8... Bxf4 9. exf4 Ne7 10. c3 Qd6 11. Ne5 $14 {Black still has to solve his issues with activating the bishop. Tsirulnik,A-Shepeleva,S Ukraine 2000}) 9. c4 $1 {A well-timed break.} (9. Nbd2 e5 10. dxe5 Nxe5 {offers White no advantage.}) 9... dxc4 10. Nbd2 e5 {The only way to involve the bishop.} 11. Nxe5 Bxe5 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Bxe5 Qxe5 14. Nxc4 Qc5 15. Rc1 $14 {White has a slight but long-lasting pressure.}) (6... Nbd7 {took place in a couple of games. The d7-knight is not placed optimally and restricts Black's possibilities.} 7. Nc3 d4 $5 {An interesting try to change the route of play. Of course,the pawn is untouchable because of 9...e5.} ({After} 7... c5 8. e4 d4 9. Nb5 Ne8 10. a4 $14 {Black's minor pieces are misplaced.}) ({Too passive is} 7... c6 8. e4 Nh5 9. Bd2 g6 10. Qe2 $14 {Black's setup was crumpled in Yankelevich,L - Ramsdal,J Copenhagen 2021}) (7... b6 8. Nb5 Ne8 (8... c5 9. Bc7 Qe8 10. Nd6 $18 {Kerecsenyi,Z - Zakaria,A LSS email 2017}) 9. c4 c6 10. cxd5 $1 cxd5 ({Bad is} 10... cxb5 $2 11. dxe6 fxe6 12. Nd4 {Black's position collapses at once.}) 11. Rc1 $14) 8. Nb5 Nd5 9. Nbxd4 {White doesn't fear of ghosts.} Nxf4 10. gxf4 c5 11. Nb5 $14 {Despite damaging White's pawn structure, Black doesn't seem to have adequate compensation for a pawn.}) (6... Bd6 {took place in 3 GM's games, so it is definitely worth attention} 7. Bxd6 cxd6 {Black keeps his central pawns compact to strengthen control of key squares e5 and c5.} ({After} 7... Qxd6 8. c4 d4 9. b4 $1 a5 10. b5 Nbd7 11. Nbd2 e5 12. a4 Nc5 13. Nb3 $14 {White seized lots of space on the Q-side, while Black's bishop is still problematic. Rapport,R - Kryvoruchko,Y Germany 2022}) 8. c4 Nc6 {This was Triapishko,A - Sjugirov,S Sochi 2021 Here I like the following new idea:} 9. e3 $5 $146 {White prevents ...d5-d4 and invites Black to show his cards.} e5 {The most challenging move. Black is trying to free himself.} ({After} 9... dxc4 10. dxc4 d5 11. Nbd2 $14 {Black still has to solve issues with his bishop.}) 10. Nc3 Be6 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Ng5 $1 {A decent tactical resource.} Nxc3 (12... Qxg5 13. Nxd5 Qd8 14. Qa4 $14 {also keeps Black under positional pressure.}) 13. Nxe6 Nxd1 14. Nxd8 Rfxd8 15. Rfxd1 $14 {White's bishop is superior to Black's knight.}) 7. c4 {White aims to open up the position before Black develops his q-side pieces.} ({This time another thematic advance} 7. e4 {seems less attractive in view of} dxe4 8. dxe4 Bb7 9. e5 Qxd1 10. Rxd1 Nd5 11. Bg5 Bxg5 12. Nxg5 h6 {The endgame was roughly equal in Grischuk,A - Dominguez Perez,L Moscow 2019}) 7... Bb7 8. Nc3 c5 {The most active and challenging choice. From now White has to do with a potential ...d5-d4 advance.} ({The attempt to simplify the matters by means of} 8... dxc4 9. dxc4 Qxd1 10. Rfxd1 {leads to an unpleasant position as White's pieces are much more active. For instance,} Rc8 11. h3 Nbd7 12. g4 $14) (8... Nbd7 {is well met by} 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Nxd5 Bxd5 {This was Volovitch,V-Wyrwich,M Germany 1997} (10... exd5 11. d4 {traditionally offers White a comfortable play against Black's isolated pawn or hanging pawns.}) {White should have played} 11. e4 $146 Bb7 12. Qe2 c5 13. Rfd1 Ba6 14. Qc2 $14 {White's pieces are placed better, and ..d3-d4 is to follow soon.}) ({Too passive is} 8... a6 9. Ne5 Nbd7 10. d4 Rc8 {, as in Radosavljevic,S - Mendonca,L Paracin 2020 Now the simple} 11. cxd5 $146 exd5 12. Bh3 $36 {would have put Black in a difficult position.}) 9. e4 d4 $146 {I find it important to keep analyzing this position: after all Black has seized lots of space.} ({In case Black grabs the pawn with} 9... dxc4 10. dxc4 Nxe4 11. Qxd8 Rxd8 12. Ng5 {the pin along the h1-a8 diagonal starts to cause him certain problems. For instance,} Bxg5 ({After} 12... Nxg5 13. Bxb7 Nh3+ 14. Kg2 Nxf4+ 15. gxf4 Nd7 16. Bxa8 Rxa8 17. Rad1 $16 {White has good chances for converting his material advantage. Hughes,D - Naeter,B IECC email 1999}) 13. Bxg5 Rd4 14. Be3 $1 {White sacrifices another pawn to get Black's rook out of play.} Rxc4 15. Rfd1 Na6 16. a3 $36 {White's initiative overwhelms the missing pawns.}) 10. Nb1 Nc6 11. e5 $1 {It is important to split the pawns and prevent the further ...e6-e5 advance from Black's side.} Nd7 12. h4 {A standard approach: White secures the f4-bishop by preventing...g7-g5.} f6 {Black reasonably initiates sharp play on the K-side to free himself.} ({The quieter} 12... Qc7 13. Re1 a6 14. Nbd2 b5 15. Qe2 Rab8 16. Rac1 $14 {doesn't leave many Black counter-chances and leaves the black king under definite pressure.}) 13. exf6 gxf6 ({After} 13... Bxf6 14. Nbd2 e5 15. Bg5 $14 {White's chances are better due to control of e4.}) 14. Nbd2 Kg7 {h6 isn't vacant for the bishop, so Black is threatening to trap it with ...e6-e5.} ({The alternatives are:} 14... Kh8 15. Bh3 $1 e5 16. Bh6 Rf7 17. Ne4 $36 {The activity of White's minor pieces makes Black's position very uncomfortable.}) (14... Rf7 15. Nh2 $1 {White manages to effectively regroup his pieces and unblock the g2-bishop.} e5 16. Bh6 Bf8 17. Qh5 {White has promising attacking prospects.}) 15. g4 {Clearing the diagonal for the f4-bishop and intending to weaken Black's king with g4-g5.} e5 {It is hard to do without this move because Black needs to connect his rooks.} 16. Bg3 Qc7 17. Qe2 {White does the same.} Kh8 18. Rae1 Rg8 19. Nh2 $14 {A complex struggle is ahead, but I prefer White's chances due to control over the light squares.} *

