{[%evp 0,33,26,23,23,0,0,0,5,5,7,-3,19,9,28,-14,-20,-35,-24,-15,-15,-7,-7,-5,-5,-5,-12,-13,0,-19,-19,-10,-23,-10,-10,-12]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O Be7 5. d3 O-O 6. Bf4 c5 {The most common reaction on White's original 6th move. Black is pretending to build a pawn center in the long run.} 7. a4 $5 {A deep idea. White prevents the possible ...b7-b5 and secures a3 for his queen's knight. Also, it is a sort of preparation for further pawn sacrifice.} ({The immediate} 7. e4 {is well met by} dxe4 8. dxe4 Nxe4 9. Qe2 Nf6 10. Rd1 Qb6 11. Na3 Nc6 {White's compensation for a pawn was questionable in Chigaev,M - Baskakov,E Lichess.org INT 2020}) 7... Nc6 {This is what Black has played in all the games so far.} ({I've also considered:} 7... Nh5 8. Bd2 Nc6 9. e4 {Of course, White has no reason for deviating from this central advance any longer.} Nf6 10. Re1 dxe4 ({After} 10... b6 11. e5 Nd7 12. Na3 Bb7 13. c3 a6 14. h4 $14 {White has great prospects on the k-side, while Black struggles to achieve anything on the opposite side.}) 11. dxe4 e5 {Black fixes the pawn structure and activates his bishop, but it costs him weakening d5.} 12. Nc3 Be6 ({After} 12... h6 13. Nd5 Be6 14. Bc3 $1 $36 {White has the superior piece coordination, and the e5-pawn is a cause of worries.}) 13. Bg5 h6 ({In case of} 13... Qxd1 14. Raxd1 h6 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Nd5 $14 {the presence of strong d5-knight doesn't allow Black to fully solve his issues.}) 14. Bxf6 Qxd1 15. Raxd1 Bxf6 16. Nd5 $14 {White has a slight positional advantage due to his strong centralized knight.}) (7... b6 8. e4 {This move is especially attractive after Black weakens the long diagonal.} dxe4 {The only way to justify the early fianchetto.} (8... Bb7 9. e5 Nfd7 10. h4 $14 {is very passive for Black.}) 9. dxe4 Ba6 {Black gains a tempo, but the a6-bishop isn't so effective.} 10. Re1 Qxd1 11. Rxd1 Nc6 12. Na3 $1 {The most flexible - White keeps c2-c3 as an option.} Rad8 13. Ne5 $14 {White has better prospects due to his active pieces.}) 8. e4 $1 {The most promising continuation. Now Black is at crossroads.} dxe4 {Black accepts the challenge. After all, the central pawn is valuable.} (8... Nh5 9. Bd2 Nf6 {transposes to 7...Nh5.}) (8... b6 {is well met by} 9. e5 Nd7 10. h4 $1 {Securing the f4-bishop and intending to extend on the k-side.} f6 {A reasonable idea - Black is trying to release the pressure on his king by getting rid of e5-pawn.} ({After} 10... Bb7 11. Re1 a6 12. Na3 Re8 13. c3 $14 {White has excellent attacking prospects in Zvjaginsev,V - Grebnev,A Moscow 2022}) 11. exf6 Bxf6 12. Nc3 Re8 13. Re1 $14 {Black's pawn structure was problematic in Andreikin,D - Thavandiran,S Chess.com INT 2022}) (8... d4 {An ambitious, but very committing move - Black's pieces are not optimally placed for switching to reversed KID.} 9. Na3 Nd7 10. Nc4 {It is very important not to allow the consolidating ...e6-e5, so the c8-bishop remains passive.} f6 {This was Andreikin,D - Girel,J Chess.com INT 2022 In my opinion, White could have claimed the misplaced d7-knight by means of} 11. Nd6 $146 g5 ({After} 11... e5 12. Nxc8 Qxc8 13. Bd2 $36 {White's light-squared bishop will be especially strong on h3.}) 12. Nxc8 Rxc8 13. Bd2 Kh8 14. Ne1 $14 {White's chances seem superior in this complex middlegame because the bishop pair should tell in the long run. White will next play f2-f4 and open the position.}) 9. dxe4 Nxe4 (9... Qxd1 10. Rxd1 Nxe4 11. Ne5 Nxe5 12. Bxe5 {transposes to 9...Nxe4.}) 10. Ne5 {White significantly activates his light-squared bishop.} Nxe5 11. Bxe5 Nd6 $1 {The best continuation. This position occurred in Andreikin,D - Saydaliev,S Chess.com INT 2022} (11... Qxd1 12. Rxd1 Bf6 {took place in Carlsen,M - Ding,L chess24.com INT 2022 Here I suggest the following idea:} 13. f4 $146 Bxe5 14. fxe5 f5 {The only way to liberate the almost trapped knight.} 15. Bxe4 fxe4 16. Nd2 e3 17. Nc4 e2 18. Rd2 $14 {White will regain the pawn and obtain a better endgame as the knight is superior over Black's bishop.}) 12. Qe2 $146 {I like this flexible continuation. White vacates d1 for his rook when the white knight has some good prospects, too.} f6 {Black is trying to free himself, although this advance makes the K-side setup somewhat dicey.} (12... Nf5 13. Rd1 Qe8 14. Na3 $44 {also provides White interesting play for a pawn, when Black's q-side pieces are paralyzed by strong g2-bishop.}) 13. Bxd6 $1 {White shouldn't regret confessing to his bishop - the main task is preventing Black from completing development.} ({Less energetic is} 13. Bc3 e5 14. Nd2 Bf5 {, and Black is doing well.}) 13... Bxd6 {The most natural recapture.} (13... Qxd6 14. Nc3 Rb8 15. Nb5 Qa6 16. c4 {also offers White promising play for a pawn as the black queen is stuck, and it is not easy for Black to connect his rooks.}) 14. Rd1 Qe7 ({Worse is} 14... Qc7 $6 15. Na3 a6 16. Nc4 Be7 17. a5 $16 {White's pieces dominate over the board.}) 15. Na3 a6 (15... Bc7 {leads to approximately the same after} 16. Rd2 a6 17. Nc4 $44) 16. Nc4 Bc7 17. a5 $44 {White keeps a long-termed compensation for a pawn due to his active minor pieces and control over the d-file.} *

