{[%evp 0,33,26,23,23,0,-9,-6,0,0,-6,8,7,0,0,-98,42,42,52,57,46,44,64,82,82,69,69,69,67,67,67,68,68,71,68,65]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nc6 {This ambitious continuation is among Black's most common weapons in Reti nowadays. Of course, Black intends to build the pawn center with e7-e5.} 3. d4 {I believe this is the only way to challenge Black's approach.} Nf6 ({The other relatively rare natural move is} 3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O Nf6 (5... e6 {was tested many times on the GM level. Still, locking the c8-bishop is hardly a good strategy. For instance,} 6. c3 Nge7 ({Or} 6... Nf6 7. Nbd2 O-O 8. Re1 b6 9. e4 $14) 7. Nbd2 O-O 8. e4 dxe4 9. Nxe4 b6 10. Re1 $14 {Black's setup was rather cramped in Banusz,T - Korpa,B Ajka 2021}) 6. b3 {I like this solid way of development. Instead, 6.c4 leads to a well-known Grunfeld tabiya.} O-O 7. Bb2 Re8 ({After} 7... Bf5 8. c4 e6 9. e3 Ne4 10. Nh4 $14 {Black's light-squared bishop feels certainly displaced. Dalton,J-Ciobanu,S Iasi 2012}) ({The other active try is} 7... Ne4 8. c4 Be6 {, but the e4-knight feels very unstable. Indeed, after} 9. cxd5 Bxd5 10. e3 Qd7 {Neale,G - Vachtfeidl,P England 2018 White could have successfully regroupped his forces by means of} 11. Ne1 $146 Rad8 12. f3 Nd6 13. Nd3 $14 {White has a superior pawn structure.}) 8. Nbd2 ({Instead,} 8. c4 dxc4 $1 9. bxc4 e5 10. d5 e4 {offers Black decent counter-play in the centre.}) 8... e5 9. Nxe5 Nxe5 10. dxe5 Ng4 {We have been following the game Carlsen,M - Van Foreest,J Oslo 2022 Here I suggest the following new idea:} 11. c4 $146 d4 12. Nf3 c5 13. b4 $1 {White is just on time to get rid of annoying d4-pawn.} Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Rxe5 15. e3 $14 {White's superior development starts to tell.}) 4. Bg2 Bf5 ({Clearly worse is} 4... Bg4 5. Ne5 $1 Bf5 6. c4 e6 7. Qa4 Bb4+ 8. Nc3 $16 {The pin along the a4-e8 diagonal causes Black lots of problems.}) 5. O-O e6 (5... Nb4 {isn't as effective as in the main lines as White isn't forced to cover c2:} 6. c4 $1 Nc2 $2 (6... e6 {is covered below.}) 7. Nh4 Nxa1 8. Nxf5 e6 9. Ne3 {The black knight is trapped and will fall very soon. White seems to have a huge advantage.}) (5... Qd7 {The attempt to exchange the bishops with ...Bh3 fails to} 6. c4 $1 e6 ({In case of} 6... dxc4 7. Na3 O-O-O 8. Nxc4 {Black's king gets in big danger because of powerful g2-bishop. The play might continue:} Nxd4 9. Nxd4 Qxd4 10. Qb3 Be4 11. Be3 {White has a decisive attack.}) 7. Nc3 O-O-O 8. Bg5 Be7 9. Qa4 Kb8 {Brenneur,R - Lavanant,A Bretagne 2001} 10. Rfc1 $146 h6 ({After} 10... Ne4 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. cxd5 exd5 13. Nxe4 $1 dxe4 14. Rxc6 {White is first to develop a powerful attack against Black's king:} exf3 15. Bxf3 Bd7 16. Qb3 $40) 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. e3 g5 13. Nd2 Ne7 14. Qb3 $36 {The better piece coordination provides White excellent attacking chances.}) 6. c4 Nb4 (6... Be7 7. Nc3 Ne4 {This was played twice by Magnus Carlsen.} (7... dxc4 8. Qa4 {allows White to regain the pawn in good redaction:} O-O 9. Qxc4 Nd5 10. e4 Nb6 11. Qd3 Bg4 12. Rd1 $14 {White has a clear positional advantage due to his pawn center. Boos,M - Oppel,D GER email 2011}) (7... O-O {is well met by} 8. Nh4 $1 Be4 ({In case of} 8... dxc4 9. Nxf5 exf5 10. e3 Rb8 11. Qa4 Bb4 12. Qb5 $14 {White manages to regain the pawn and maintain all his strategic merits. Demchenko,A - Kornyukov,A Armavir 2011}) 9. f3 Bg6 10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. e4 Nb6 13. Be3 Bf6 {The natural play by both sides led to this position in Praggnanandhaa,R - Bortnyk,M Chess.com INT 2020 Now White should have played} 14. e5 $1 $146 Be7 15. f4 Qd7 16. a3 Rad8 17. Ne2 $14 {White's huge space advantage and bishop pair overwhelm the d5-outpost.}) 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Nd2 $1 {White starts figting again opponent's most active piece.} ({Instead,} 9. Bf4 Nxc3 10. bxc3 Na5 {was equal in Svane,R - Carlsen,M Lichess.org INT 2020}) 9... Nf6 ({Worse is} 9... Nxd4 $6 10. Qa4+ Nc6 11. Ndxe4 dxe4 12. Nxe4 $36 {The strong g2-bishop puts Black under strong positional pressure.}) ({Or} 9... Nxc3 $6 10. bxc3 Be6 11. Rb1 Rb8 12. e4 $36 {Black's position looks very crumped in view of White's strong pawn center. Kortschnoj,V - Wirthensohn,H Nuremberg 1990}) 10. Nb3 O-O ({Too slow is} 10... h6 11. Nc5 Rb8 12. Nxd5 $1 Nxd5 13. e4 $36 {White had a powerful initiative in Johansen,J - Haug,K ICCF email 2019}) 11. Bg5 {Now the d5-pawn feels quite vulnerable.} Ne4 12. Bxe7 Nxe7 13. Nxe4 Bxe4 14. Bxe4 dxe4 15. Qc2 $14 {Black had difficulties with defending his central pawn in Denayer,W - Baticulon,N LSS email 2008}) 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Nc3 c6 ({After} 8... Nc2 $2 9. Nh4 Nxa1 10. Nxf5 {Black was practically lost in Gritsenko,V - Ponomariov,T Voronezh 2008}) 9. a3 Na6 10. Ne5 {The awkward a6-knight makes it not possible for Black to challenge the strong knight on e5 at the moment.} Be7 11. e4 $1 Be6 {We have been following the game Bernadskiy,V - Petkov,V Sunny Beach 2013} ({The tactical point of White's last move is that} 11... dxe4 $2 {runs into} 12. Qb3 O-O 13. Qxb7 $18) {Here I strongly suggest} 12. exd5 $146 Nxd5 13. f4 $1 {White grabs lots of space on the K-side.} Nxc3 {Black has to vacate d5 for his bishop. On the other hand, it strengthens White's pawn center.} 14. bxc3 O-O 15. f5 Bd5 16. Bxd5 cxd5 17. Rb1 $36 {The a6-knight is misplaced, and Black's king is in permanent danger.} *

