{[%evp 0,27,23,23,28,0,-6,-6,1,-3,25,32,71,51,51,51,48,57,66,51,47,69,77,59,94,43,29,21,48,61]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nc6 3. d4 Bg4 {This move is even slightly more popular than 3...Bf5. In some cases, Black may damage White's pawn structure with ...Bxf3 or exchange the bishops.} 4. Bg2 Qd7 {By far the most common choice. Black shows his intention to play ...Bh3 and also makes 0-0-0 possible.} (4... e6 {isn't in the spirit of Black's aggressive choice on the 2nd move. However, it was employed by many strong players, including Grischuk, Piorun and others.} 5. O-O Bd6 ({After} 5... Nf6 6. c4 dxc4 7. Nbd2 $1 Be7 (7... Nxd4 $2 8. Nxd4 Qxd4 9. Bxb7 {is even worse for Black.}) 8. Nxc4 O-O 9. Nfe5 $16 {Black got in a difficult position because of powerful g2-bishop. Gretarsson,H - Johannessen,S Gausdal 1995}) 6. c4 Nf6 7. cxd5 exd5 ({After} 7... Nxd5 8. e4 Nb6 9. Be3 O-O 10. Nbd2 $14 {Black didn't have compensation for opponent's strong pawn center in Radovanovic,M - Perunovic,M Skopje 2018}) 8. Bg5 Qd7 {The most consistent, although it is connected with a positional concession.} (8... h6 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. Nc3 Bxf3 11. Bxf3 Nxd4 12. Bxd5 $14 {leaves Black in a passive position when neutralizing the pressure along diagonal h1-a8 wouldn't be easy. Wirthensohn,H - Skembris,S Germany 2014}) 9. Bxf6 gxf6 10. Nc3 Ne7 11. Qb3 c6 12. e4 $36 {Black was in trouble in view of poor pawn structure and lack of development in Mainka,G - Breutigam,M Dortmund 1993}) (4... h5 {is premature, as was illustrated in the following game:} 5. c4 e6 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Nc3 Qd7 8. h3 Be6 9. Ng5 {The exchange of strong e6-bishop secures White an advantage. Petran,P - Horvath,S Hungary 1993}) 5. O-O {I like this energetic decision: White doesn't fear ghosts! Black is invited to follow his original plans with 5...Bh3.} ({Another logical way is} 5. h3 Bxf3 6. Bxf3 O-O-O {, but then some development advantage is on Black's side and ...e7-e5 might follow at some point.}) 5... Bh3 {A consistent but risky approach: Black delays his development for a long time!} (5... O-O-O {was seen in most of the games, but after} 6. c4 dxc4 7. Nbd2 $1 {The power of a strong Catalan bishop is very impressive. The following line illustrate White's attacking potential:} Nxd4 (7... Bh3 $146 {runs into} 8. d5 $1 Bxg2 9. dxc6 Qh3 10. cxb7+ Kxb7 11. Ng5 Qh5 12. Kxg2 Qxg5 13. Qc2 {Black's pawn structure is destroyed.}) ({Another ambitious try is} 7... f6 8. Nxc4 e5 {Petenyi,T - Tari,A Antalya 2017 and now White should have completed his development by means of} 9. Be3 $1 $146 Bxf3 ({The other possibilities are:} 9... e4 10. Nfd2 Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Qxd4 12. Bxe4 $36) ({and} 9... exd4 10. Nxd4 Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Qxd4 12. Qb3 c6 13. Rfd1 $36) 10. Bxf3 exd4 11. Bf4 g5 12. Bd2 Nge7 13. Rc1 $36 {White's initiative on the q-side overwhelms the pawn.}) 8. Nxd4 Qxd4 9. Qa4 Bxe2 {Black relies on his material advantage, but White's big development advantage prevails.} 10. Re1 Bd3 11. Nf3 Qb6 12. Be3 {Although Black is up 3 pawns, the position is practically resignable in view of} Qa6 13. Qxa6 bxa6 14. Ne5 {with a collapse.}) ({The aggressive} 5... h5 {meets} 6. c4 e6 ({After} 6... dxc4 7. Na3 h4 8. Nxc4 hxg3 9. Nce5 $1 $36 {Black suffers from lack of development.}) 7. Nc3 O-O-O (7... dxc4 {Arabidze,M - Rakhmanov,A Chess.com INT 2021 can be strongly met by} 8. Ne5 $146 Nxe5 9. dxe5 O-O-O 10. Qc2 {White is threatening 11.Rd1, so Black's next move is forced.} Bf5 11. e4 Bg6 12. Be3 $36 {White's forces are fully mobilized, while Black's K-side pieces are still on their initial spots.}) 8. Qa4 Kb8 9. cxd5 exd5 {This was Eljanov,P - Lugovskoy,M Chess.com INT 2020 Here White could have used a typical tactical idea:} 10. Nxd5 $1 $146 Bxf3 ({The naive} 10... Qxd5 $2 11. Ne5 Qe6 12. Nxc6+ bxc6 13. Bxc6 $18 {offers White a stunning attack.}) 11. Bxf3 Ne5 {Black also uses little tactics to regain the pawn, but it doesn't solve all his issues with development:} 12. Qxd7 Nxf3+ 13. exf3 Rxd7 14. Nc3 Rxd4 15. Bf4 $16 {White has a serious initiative.}) 6. c4 Bxg2 7. Kxg2 e6 ({After} 7... dxc4 8. d5 Nb4 9. e4 Nd3 10. Qc2 $16 {The only developed black piece (the d3-knight) will be neutralized soon, while Black struggles to involve his other pieces.}) 8. Nc3 Nf6 (8... O-O-O {was seen in Obregon Rivero,J - Morozevich,A Lichess.org INT 2021 White could have developed a powerful initiative with} 9. c5 $1 $146 e5 10. b4 e4 (10... exd4 11. Nb5 $40) 11. Ne1 h5 12. h4 $16 {Obviously, Black's king is in bigger danger.}) ({The other possibilities are:} 8... Bb4 {Seeman,T - Sulskis,S Tallinn 2010} 9. e4 $146 Bxc3 ({After} 9... Nge7 10. cxd5 exd5 11. e5 O-O-O 12. Ne2 Ng6 13. h4 $14 {White has a solid space advantage and good prospects along the c-file.}) 10. exd5 exd5 11. cxd5 Qxd5 12. bxc3 O-O-O 13. Qb3 $14 {White has the better chances due to his powerful pawn center.}) ({and} 8... dxc4 9. e4 O-O-O {This position occurred in Nikolenko,V - Lefebr,V Cheliabinsk 2011} 10. Qa4 $1 $146 {White regains the pawn and puts strong pressure on Black's king.} Kb8 11. d5 exd5 12. exd5 Nb4 13. Qxd7 Rxd7 14. Ne5 $16 {White has a huge positional advantage.}) 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Ne5 $1 {Black isn't in time to complete development.} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Ng4 {This was Escudero Donoso,F - Pollio,C Santiago de Chile 2012 Among White's most promising possibilities, I prefer} 12. Qb3 $5 $146 c6 ({After} 12... O-O-O 13. Bf4 d4 14. Nb5 a6 15. Nxc7 {Black's position collapses.}) 13. Bf4 Bc5 14. Rad1 $16 {The g4-knight is in trouble, and the opposition on the d-file causes Black lots of problems.} *

