{[%evp 0,39,24,28,27,-6,-6,0,0,0,0,6,27,-10,4,10,10,10,10,18,24,28,21,21,30,45,45,52,59,59,51,58,13,23,23,23,40,49,42,40,39,37]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nc6 3. d4 Bf5 4. Bg2 e6 {A quiet choice. Black goes for a quick development and leaves ...Nc6-b4 as an option in the long run.} 5. O-O Nb4 (5... Nf6 6. c4 {transposes to 2...Nc6 3.d4}) 6. Ne1 {6.Na3 is much more common, but this isn't our choice after 4...Nb4. Also, I like this flexible way of covering the c2-pawn.} Be7 {The most flexible choice. By starting with this move, Black eliminates the early ..Bc1-g5.} ({The quieter alternative is} 6... Nf6 7. c3 Nc6 ({Doesn't change much} 7... Na6 8. Bg5 Be7 9. Nd2 O-O 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. e4 dxe4 12. Nxe4 $14 {Black has a solid, but very passive position. Banusz,T - Blohberger,F Reykjavik 2021}) 8. Bg5 Be7 9. Nd2 O-O 10. Bxf6 $1 {White correctly confesses to his bishop to activate the other one.} Bxf6 11. e4 dxe4 12. Nxe4 Bxe4 13. Bxe4 $14 {The pressure along the long diagonal felt quite annoying in Oparin,G - Lagarde,M Chalons en Champagne 2021}) ({The aggressive} 6... h5 {doesn't seem to work} 7. c4 h4 $146 {The most natural follow-up.} ({Inconsistent is} 7... c6 8. Nc3 Nf6 9. Qb3 Qd7 10. a3 Na6 11. Nf3 $16 {Black is left with poor a6-knight and exposed k-side in view of weakening ...h7-h5.Vigorito,D - Oberoi,S Charlotte 2022}) 8. Nc3 hxg3 9. fxg3 $1 {White needs to keep the h-file locked and involve the rook.} dxc4 10. Bxb7 Rb8 11. Bg2 $16 {Black's q-side is ruined.}) 7. c3 {The active b4-knight should be chased away.} Nc6 8. Nd3 {The d3-knight is well-placed as it keep an eye on both c5 and e5.} Nf6 9. Re1 {A flexible continuation. White intends to push e2-e4 at some point but leaves the c1-bishop unblocked for a while.} a5 {Black is interested in keeping his king in the center for a while. This move is aimed at preventing the potential ..b2-b4 advance.} ({The more obvious} 9... O-O {is met by} 10. Nd2 Qd7 ({After} 10... Bxd3 11. exd3 Bd6 12. Nf3 $14 {Black lacks any counterplay, while White can start advancing his pawns after the knight will land on e5.}) 11. e4 dxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Bxe4 Bxe4 14. Rxe4 Rad8 15. Qe2 $14 {White has a slight but long-lasting advantage because Black fails to challenge the center with c7-c5 or e6-e5.}) 10. Bg5 $5 $146 {This natural move is a novelty. By exchanging the f6-knight, White makes the thematic e2-e4 advance more effective.} ({The previously played} 10. Nd2 h5 $1 11. e4 dxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Bxe4 Bxe4 14. Rxe4 Qd5 15. Qf3 O-O-O $132 {led to a double-edged play in Svane,R -Yu,Y chess.com INT 2023}) 10... O-O ({After} 10... Nd7 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. e4 dxe4 13. Bxe4 Bxe4 14. Rxe4 $14 {Black struggles to solve his issues with space.}) 11. Nd2 Ne4 $5 {A radical way to stop e2-e4.} ({Another try is} 11... Bxd3 12. exd3 h6 13. Be3 Bd6 14. Nf3 $14 {, but then White's bishop pair seems to tell in the long run: White has few potential ideas such as ..c3-c4 or g3-g4 break, while Black's counterplay is questionable.}) 12. Bxe7 Nxe7 13. Nxe4 Bxe4 (13... dxe4 $2 14. Nc5 Qd5 15. f3 {leads to material losses.}) 14. Bxe4 dxe4 15. Nc5 Qd5 {The only way to maintain the material balance. Statically, Black's position looks fine.} 16. Qc2 f5 {A committing move, but Black has no choice.} 17. f3 $1 {A well-times break.} b6 18. fxe4 Qc6 19. Nb3 fxe4 20. Nd2 $14 {Black has no compensation for his structural drawbacks.} *

