{[%evp 0,43,33,27,27,0,0,0,0,-8,35,35,29,29,29,33,32,27,17,0,-1,-1,17,-1,43,-1,13,20,21,21,21,21,21,33,63,63,63,47,67,34,34,34,34,34,41,22]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nc6 3. d4 Bf5 4. Bg2 Nb4 {This ambitious approach has become very popular recently. By attacking the c2-pawn, Black provokes the awkward Nb1-a3, interrupting White's traditional plan with c2-c4. On the downside, Black's development is heavily delayed.} 5. Na3 e6 ({The other consolidating move} 5... c6 {also runs into} 6. Nh4 $1 Bg4 7. h3 Be6 ({After} 7... Bh5 8. c3 Na6 9. Qb3 Qb6 10. g4 Bg6 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. e4 $14 {Black had no compensation for opponent's strong unoposed g2-bishop in Tunik,G - Barskij,V Yalta 1996}) 8. c3 Na6 {This position occurred in Kamsky,G - Godena,M Reggio Emilia 2009 In my opinion, White could have claimed the drawbacks of opponent's setup by means of} 9. e4 $1 $146 dxe4 10. Bxe4 Nf6 11. Bg2 Bd5 12. Nf3 {This pawn structure is often acceptable for Black in case he can challenge the center with ...c6-c5. However, the poor a6-knight makes it problematic in this case.} e6 13. Nc2 Be7 ({After} 13... c5 14. O-O cxd4 15. Ncxd4 Bc5 16. c4 $14 {White has a superior piece coordination.}) 14. Qe2 O-O 15. O-O $14 {Black faces some concrete problems in view of upcoming c3-c4.}) (5... Nf6 {is less flexible than 5...e6 in view of} 6. c3 Nc6 7. Ne5 $1 {The e5-knight is untouchable, yielding White stability in the center.} e6 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Qa4 Qd7 {The natural play by both sides led to this position in Guilhon,F - De Oliveira,J Sao Paulo 2022 White could have put strong pressure on Black's weaknesses by means of} 10. Nc4 $1 $146 c5 (10... Bd6 11. Ne5 Bxe5 12. dxe5 Ng4 13. Bf4 {is very for Black, whose king is still in the center while the g4-knight is in big danger.}) 11. Qa6 Bd6 {Black has to parry the threat of 12.Ne5.} 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. Ne5 {Still, the centralized knight causes Black definite problems.} Qd6 14. Qb5+ Ke7 15. Nc6+ Kd7 {The only move! There is no decisive discovery.} 16. Nd4+ c6 17. Qa4 $36 {Black's king is in big danger.}) ({Too slow is} 5... h6 $6 {Black secures h7 for his bishop, but it costs him a viable tempo.} 6. c3 Na6 7. Qb3 Rb8 {This occurred in Rapport,J - Djukic,S Pancevo 2011 Here I suggest} 8. Nh4 $146 Be6 (8... Be4 9. Bxe4 dxe4 10. f3 exf3 11. O-O $16 {White's lead in development prevails.}) 9. f4 g6 10. O-O Nf6 11. f5 $16 {Black struggles to develop his k-side.}) 6. Nh4 {I mostly like this move, even though it is only 3rd White's choice in practice. The exchange of the f5-bishop can be considered a certain achievement in most cases.} Bg4 (6... Be4 {Provoking f2-f3 is a double-edged measure: White's minor pieces are less active, but it supports the key e2-e4 advance.} 7. f3 Bg6 8. c3 Nc6 9. Qb3 Rb8 ({The alternative way of covering the b7-pawn is} 9... a6 10. e4 Na5 11. Qd1 Bh5 (11... Bxa3 12. Qa4+ b5 13. Qxa3 Nc4 14. Qc5 $36) 12. exd5 exd5 $146 {I find this recapture most sensible.} ({Bad is} 12... g5 $2 13. Qa4+ c6 14. dxc6 Nxc6 15. Bxg5 Qxg5 16. f4 $18 {Black was fully destroyed in view of 17.Bxc6+. Loeffler,S - Pechac,J Austria 2022}) 13. O-O Bxa3 {A sad necessity. Black confesses to his bishop in order to castle soon.} 14. Qa4+ Nc6 15. Qxa3 Nge7 16. Bh3 O-O 17. Qb3 $14 {In this kind of middlegame, White's bishop pair is gonna be a viable factor.}) 10. e4 b5 {An ambitious idea: Black restricts the mobility of White's q-side pieces and intends to push ...b5-b4 at some point.} ({Another considerable option is} 10... Be7 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. Nc2 Nf6 {This was Yermolinsky,A - Friedel,J Berkeley 2005 Here I mostly like} 13. Qb5 $5 $146 {White re-locates his somewhat awkward Qb3} Qd7 (13... a6 14. Qe2 Na5 15. b3 $14) 14. Qe2 b5 15. e5 Ng8 16. b4 $14 {Black desperately lacks space.}) 11. Nxg6 hxg6 {This was Sagit,R - Hector,J Eskilstuna 2019 In my opinion, it was a good moment for regrouping the forces:} 12. Nb1 $1 $146 Nf6 13. Nd2 Na5 ({After} 13... Be7 14. Qd1 b4 15. O-O O-O 16. e5 Nd7 17. f4 $14 {White has a big space advantage and great attacking chances - g3-g4 will follow soon.}) 14. Qc2 c5 15. dxc5 Qc7 {A tricky idea - Black is eyeing the g3-pawn.} (15... Bxc5 16. e5 Nd7 17. b4 {drops a piece.}) 16. b4 Rxh2 17. Nf1 $1 {An important defensive resource that allows White to cover g3.} Rxh1 18. Bxh1 Nc6 19. Bf4 $1 {By provoking e6-e5 White limits opponent's attacking abilities.} e5 20. Bd2 $14 {The strongly passed c5-pawn offers White better chances in the upcoming complex struggle.}) ({Too passive is} 6... Bg6 7. c3 Nc6 8. Qb3 Rb8 (8... Bxa3 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Qxa3 Nge7 11. e4 {is equally unpleasant for Black.}) 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. e4 Bxa3 11. Qxa3 Nge7 12. O-O {Black was doomed to passive defense because both White's bishops were much stronger than knights. To,N - Ongut,T Hungary 2018}) 7. c3 Nc6 8. Qb3 Rb8 (8... Na5 $6 {is pointless as after} 9. Qa4+ c6 $2 10. b4 {Black suffers heavy material losses.}) ({Hardly better is also} 8... Bxa3 9. Qxa3 Qe7 10. Qa4 Nf6 11. b4 $36 {The unoposed dark-squared bishop will be especially effective on the a3-f8 diagonal.}) 9. e4 $1 {This advance is well-timed - otherwise the early Nf3-h4 turns useless.} dxe4 ({Black shouldn't ignore the last move with} 9... Nf6 $6 10. h3 Bh5 11. exd5 exd5 12. g4 Bg6 13. Bg5 $16 {The d5-pawn is very weak.}) 10. Bxe4 Be7 (10... Nf6 11. Bg2 Be7 12. Nc4 {is covered below.}) 11. Nc4 Bh3 {This move is aimed at preventing ..0-0.} ({After} 11... Nf6 12. Bg2 O-O 13. O-O Nd5 14. Nf3 Bxf3 {Black captures the knight before it lands on e5.} 15. Bxf3 Bg5 16. Re1 Bxc1 17. Raxc1 $14 {White has a stable positional advantage due to his strong bishop and definite space advantage. Praggnanandhaa,R - Saric,I Caleta 2020}) ({I also examined} 11... Bxh4 $146 12. gxh4 Nf6 {Black managed to damage White's pawn structure at the cost of the dark-squared bishop. On the other hand, White can now benefit from opening the g-file.} 13. Bg5 $1 {The most energetic. There is no need to waste a tempo from retreating the bishop.} Qd7 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. f3 $1 {The last preparation before casting.} Bh5 16. d5 exd5 17. O-O-O $36 {White has a powerful initiative because Black's king is stuck in the center.}) 12. Ng2 Nf6 13. Bf3 Bg4 14. Bxg4 ({Weaker is} 14. Qd1 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 Qd5 $11) 14... Nxg4 15. a4 {A decent move. Black's only active idea is pushing the Q-side pawns.} a6 16. O-O b5 ({After} 16... O-O 17. Qc2 Nf6 18. Bg5 b5 19. Nd2 $14 {White has a slight but long-lasting positional advantage because Black's setup on the q-side is exposed.}) 17. axb5 axb5 18. Nce3 Nf6 {We have been following the game Predojevic,B - Krstulovic,A Vrnjacka Banja 2022 White could have developed his initiative by means of} 19. d5 $1 $146 exd5 20. Rd1 d4 (20... O-O 21. Nxd5 Nxd5 22. Rxd5 Bd6 23. Bf4 {also puts Black under strong positional pressure because of pinned d6-bishop.}) 21. Nf5 O-O 22. cxd4 $14 {The strong f5-knight offers White the better prospects.} *

